WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.458 align:middle line:90%


00:00:01.458 --> 00:00:02.430 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.430 --> 00:00:03.888 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.888 --> 00:00:05.832 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:05.832 --> 00:00:12.160 align:middle line:90%


00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:14.780 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: We have
seen, I would say,

00:00:14.780 --> 00:00:17.720 align:middle line:84%
three sets of tools applied
to the problem of projection

00:00:17.720 --> 00:00:18.373 align:middle line:90%
theory.

00:00:18.373 --> 00:00:20.040 align:middle line:84%
So at the beginning
of the class, first,

00:00:20.040 --> 00:00:22.360 align:middle line:90%
we talked about double counting.

00:00:22.360 --> 00:00:25.480 align:middle line:84%
And then we talked about
methods from Fourier analysis.

00:00:25.480 --> 00:00:28.120 align:middle line:84%
And then in the last week,
we started our third set

00:00:28.120 --> 00:00:32.080 align:middle line:84%
of tools which are tools from
combinatorial number theory.

00:00:32.080 --> 00:00:36.000 align:middle line:84%
So this week we're
going to finish our unit

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:37.720 align:middle line:84%
on tools from
combinatorial number

00:00:37.720 --> 00:00:41.332 align:middle line:90%
theory in projection theory.

00:00:41.332 --> 00:00:48.240 align:middle line:84%
So the goal for these two weeks
is this projection theorem

00:00:48.240 --> 00:00:51.080 align:middle line:90%
of Bourgain, Katz, and Tao.

00:00:51.080 --> 00:00:53.220 align:middle line:84%
It takes place
over finite fields,

00:00:53.220 --> 00:00:55.880 align:middle line:84%
and the cool thing about it is
that it distinguishes what's

00:00:55.880 --> 00:00:57.400 align:middle line:84%
true over prime
fields from what's

00:00:57.400 --> 00:01:00.370 align:middle line:84%
true over other fields, which
none of our previous methods

00:01:00.370 --> 00:01:01.630 align:middle line:90%
could distinguish.

00:01:01.630 --> 00:01:06.010 align:middle line:90%


00:01:06.010 --> 00:01:09.385 align:middle line:90%
This is our goal.

00:01:09.385 --> 00:01:15.890 align:middle line:84%
It says that if x is a
subset of Fp squared,

00:01:15.890 --> 00:01:18.670 align:middle line:90%
and it has size p to the sx--

00:01:18.670 --> 00:01:21.130 align:middle line:84%
you can think of sx
like a dimension--

00:01:21.130 --> 00:01:23.590 align:middle line:90%
and sx is in between 0 and 2.

00:01:23.590 --> 00:01:26.170 align:middle line:84%
So it's not too tiny,
and it's not everything.

00:01:26.170 --> 00:01:29.850 align:middle line:84%
And we have a set
of directions in Fp,

00:01:29.850 --> 00:01:33.900 align:middle line:84%
a set of directions as size p to
the sd, and it's not too tiny.

00:01:33.900 --> 00:01:38.090 align:middle line:90%


00:01:38.090 --> 00:01:41.250 align:middle line:84%
Then, if I take the
maximum over all

00:01:41.250 --> 00:01:44.330 align:middle line:84%
of the directions of the
size of the projection

00:01:44.330 --> 00:01:48.250 align:middle line:84%
in that direction,
it's at least--

00:01:48.250 --> 00:01:51.250 align:middle line:90%
so the square root of x.

00:01:51.250 --> 00:01:53.770 align:middle line:84%
So far, that's not
difficult to do.

00:01:53.770 --> 00:01:56.570 align:middle line:84%
But then plus-- times
a little bit more,

00:01:56.570 --> 00:01:58.820 align:middle line:90%
times p to the epsilon.

00:01:58.820 --> 00:01:59.980 align:middle line:90%
I'll call it epsilon--

00:01:59.980 --> 00:02:01.320 align:middle line:90%
p to the epsilon.

00:02:01.320 --> 00:02:08.820 align:middle line:84%
So this epsilon depends on these
dimensions, but it's positive.

00:02:08.820 --> 00:02:10.300 align:middle line:90%
So that's our goal.

00:02:10.300 --> 00:02:14.260 align:middle line:84%
And it's significant
that this would not

00:02:14.260 --> 00:02:16.020 align:middle line:90%
be true in other fields.

00:02:16.020 --> 00:02:26.540 align:middle line:84%
So this is false in Fq
squared if q equals p squared.

00:02:26.540 --> 00:02:37.180 align:middle line:84%
And the example is that x
is Fp squared, and D is Fp.

00:02:37.180 --> 00:02:39.560 align:middle line:84%
And so then this
thing is always Fp.

00:02:39.560 --> 00:02:45.700 align:middle line:90%


00:02:45.700 --> 00:02:46.420 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:02:46.420 --> 00:02:51.020 align:middle line:84%
So even though this epsilon
is a really tiny number, which

00:02:51.020 --> 00:02:52.920 align:middle line:84%
we could make explicit
if we worked hard,

00:02:52.920 --> 00:02:55.180 align:middle line:84%
but we would then
be disappointed.

00:02:55.180 --> 00:02:58.590 align:middle line:84%
Even though it's really
tiny, this theorem

00:02:58.590 --> 00:03:01.350 align:middle line:84%
is qualitatively an
important improvement,

00:03:01.350 --> 00:03:03.910 align:middle line:90%
and it has lots of applications.

00:03:03.910 --> 00:03:06.192 align:middle line:84%
This and the version over r
have lots of applications,

00:03:06.192 --> 00:03:08.150 align:middle line:84%
and almost everything in
the rest of the course

00:03:08.150 --> 00:03:11.670 align:middle line:84%
will be based on that, kind of
whatever most of the directions

00:03:11.670 --> 00:03:12.490 align:middle line:90%
we might go in.

00:03:12.490 --> 00:03:18.550 align:middle line:90%


00:03:18.550 --> 00:03:23.150 align:middle line:84%
All right, so last week, we
introduced combinatorial number

00:03:23.150 --> 00:03:24.890 align:middle line:90%
theory and some product theory.

00:03:24.890 --> 00:03:29.110 align:middle line:84%
And we proved a theorem,
which is in this direction.

00:03:29.110 --> 00:03:30.710 align:middle line:84%
It's kind of the
special case when

00:03:30.710 --> 00:03:32.270 align:middle line:90%
x happens to be a product set--

00:03:32.270 --> 00:03:39.590 align:middle line:84%
A cross A. So our Theorem 1
was last time, if A is in Fp,

00:03:39.590 --> 00:03:45.510 align:middle line:84%
and the size of
A is p to the sa,

00:03:45.510 --> 00:03:52.270 align:middle line:84%
and D is the set of directions
in Fp, and size of D

00:03:52.270 --> 00:03:53.750 align:middle line:90%
is p to the sd.

00:03:53.750 --> 00:03:57.960 align:middle line:90%


00:03:57.960 --> 00:04:04.520 align:middle line:84%
Then, if you take the
maximum t and D, of A plus t

00:04:04.520 --> 00:04:09.520 align:middle line:84%
times A, which would be
like pi sub t of A cross A,

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:15.300 align:middle line:84%
then that's at least the size
of A times p to the epsilon 1.

00:04:15.300 --> 00:04:21.360 align:middle line:90%


00:04:21.360 --> 00:04:22.560 align:middle line:90%
That's a little bit bigger.

00:04:22.560 --> 00:04:25.640 align:middle line:84%
And this, again, would
be false in other fields.

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:27.960 align:middle line:84%
So if our field
had a subfield, you

00:04:27.960 --> 00:04:30.140 align:middle line:84%
could choose these guys
to both be the subfield.

00:04:30.140 --> 00:04:31.640 align:middle line:84%
And this would stay
in the subfield.

00:04:31.640 --> 00:04:34.640 align:middle line:90%


00:04:34.640 --> 00:04:36.080 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:04:36.080 --> 00:04:43.075 align:middle line:84%
All right, so our goal today
is to get from here to there.

00:04:43.075 --> 00:04:44.700 align:middle line:84%
And we were talking
about it last time,

00:04:44.700 --> 00:04:46.367 align:middle line:84%
and I wanted to-- so
at first this looks

00:04:46.367 --> 00:04:48.400 align:middle line:90%
like a very special case.

00:04:48.400 --> 00:04:50.860 align:middle line:84%
I'll try to argue that it's
only a little bit special case,

00:04:50.860 --> 00:04:52.620 align:middle line:90%
and we'll see what the issue is.

00:04:52.620 --> 00:05:01.970 align:middle line:90%


00:05:01.970 --> 00:05:12.030 align:middle line:84%
We call this an attempt
at BKT using Theorem 1.

00:05:12.030 --> 00:05:15.010 align:middle line:90%


00:05:15.010 --> 00:05:19.970 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to do a
proof by contradiction.

00:05:19.970 --> 00:05:23.330 align:middle line:84%
We're going to say
epsilon is very small,

00:05:23.330 --> 00:05:27.090 align:middle line:90%
and it's to be decided.

00:05:27.090 --> 00:05:36.090 align:middle line:84%
And so then we'll assume
that pi t of x is less than x

00:05:36.090 --> 00:05:39.990 align:middle line:84%
to the half times p to the
epsilon for all the ts in D.

00:05:39.990 --> 00:05:43.210 align:middle line:84%
So proof by contradiction,
so we can assume that.

00:05:43.210 --> 00:05:45.910 align:middle line:84%
And also, without
loss of generality,

00:05:45.910 --> 00:05:48.090 align:middle line:84%
we can suppose that
0 and infinity are

00:05:48.090 --> 00:05:50.790 align:middle line:84%
in our set of directions,
D. So in other words,

00:05:50.790 --> 00:05:53.050 align:middle line:84%
we include the
horizontal projection

00:05:53.050 --> 00:05:55.850 align:middle line:90%
and the vertical projection.

00:05:55.850 --> 00:06:00.330 align:middle line:84%
So then we can make a set,
A, so that A times A contains

00:06:00.330 --> 00:06:07.570 align:middle line:84%
x And x is most of A times A. So
the set A is pi 0 of x, union pi

00:06:07.570 --> 00:06:13.570 align:middle line:84%
infinity of x, or the size of A
bounded by size of x to the half

00:06:13.570 --> 00:06:16.050 align:middle line:90%
times p to the epsilon.

00:06:16.050 --> 00:06:24.730 align:middle line:90%
And x is contained in A times A.

00:06:24.730 --> 00:06:27.750 align:middle line:84%
So x is a big
subset of a product,

00:06:27.750 --> 00:06:29.660 align:middle line:84%
and we can apply Theorem
1 to our product.

00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:32.890 align:middle line:90%


00:06:32.890 --> 00:06:38.130 align:middle line:84%
So theorem one tells us
that the maximum t and D

00:06:38.130 --> 00:06:41.950 align:middle line:90%
of pi t of A times A is big.

00:06:41.950 --> 00:06:49.700 align:middle line:90%


00:06:49.700 --> 00:06:54.180 align:middle line:84%
And even bigger than that,
so this could be epsilon 1.

00:06:54.180 --> 00:06:57.400 align:middle line:84%
And epsilon 1 is much
bigger than epsilon.

00:06:57.400 --> 00:06:59.720 align:middle line:84%
So epsilon 1 came from a
theorem that's already proven.

00:06:59.720 --> 00:07:00.678 align:middle line:90%
It's some number.

00:07:00.678 --> 00:07:02.720 align:middle line:84%
And we get to choose
epsilon as small as we like,

00:07:02.720 --> 00:07:04.470 align:middle line:84%
so we choose it much
smaller than epsilon.

00:07:04.470 --> 00:07:09.124 align:middle line:90%


00:07:09.124 --> 00:07:13.620 align:middle line:84%
But this is not yet
the projection theorem

00:07:13.620 --> 00:07:15.740 align:middle line:90%
that we're aiming for.

00:07:15.740 --> 00:07:22.980 align:middle line:84%
And the issue is we would
like pi t of x to be big.

00:07:22.980 --> 00:07:30.100 align:middle line:84%
So the issue is, maybe pi t
of x is much smaller than pi

00:07:30.100 --> 00:07:39.100 align:middle line:84%
t of A cross A. Even though x
is a big chunk of A cross A.

00:07:39.100 --> 00:07:41.090 align:middle line:84%
Let me make a picture
of this enemy scenario.

00:07:41.090 --> 00:07:44.420 align:middle line:90%


00:07:44.420 --> 00:07:46.390 align:middle line:90%
So here's the enemy scenario.

00:07:46.390 --> 00:07:55.950 align:middle line:90%


00:07:55.950 --> 00:08:05.870 align:middle line:84%
All right, so there's a set x
which has a small projection.

00:08:05.870 --> 00:08:09.470 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to be
doing a projection, say,

00:08:09.470 --> 00:08:10.570 align:middle line:90%
in this direction.

00:08:10.570 --> 00:08:13.110 align:middle line:90%


00:08:13.110 --> 00:08:14.580 align:middle line:90%
Projection of x is small.

00:08:14.580 --> 00:08:18.070 align:middle line:90%


00:08:18.070 --> 00:08:24.910 align:middle line:84%
And x is a big portion of
this larger set, A cross A.

00:08:24.910 --> 00:08:28.910 align:middle line:84%
So in blue, we have
A cross A without x.

00:08:28.910 --> 00:08:34.220 align:middle line:84%
And when we project that down,
then we see a lot of stuff.

00:08:34.220 --> 00:08:38.792 align:middle line:90%


00:08:38.792 --> 00:08:42.590 align:middle line:90%
Pi of t, A cross A without x.

00:08:42.590 --> 00:08:45.110 align:middle line:84%
So we're worried that
we may be so unlucky

00:08:45.110 --> 00:08:47.320 align:middle line:84%
that even though
pi t of A cross A

00:08:47.320 --> 00:08:52.040 align:middle line:84%
is quite large, and even though
x is a big chunk of A cross A,

00:08:52.040 --> 00:08:54.660 align:middle line:84%
nevertheless, pi
t of x is small.

00:08:54.660 --> 00:08:55.740 align:middle line:90%
We're worried about that.

00:08:55.740 --> 00:09:04.220 align:middle line:90%


00:09:04.220 --> 00:09:09.200 align:middle line:84%
So that's where we left
off before vacation.

00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:11.760 align:middle line:84%
And now what I'd
like everyone to do

00:09:11.760 --> 00:09:14.820 align:middle line:84%
is to try to think of an
example where this happens.

00:09:14.820 --> 00:09:18.240 align:middle line:84%
Does this ever actually happen
that inside of A cross A,

00:09:18.240 --> 00:09:21.240 align:middle line:84%
you have a large subset
x, and the projection

00:09:21.240 --> 00:09:27.320 align:middle line:84%
of x is small, even though the
projection of A cross A is big?

00:09:27.320 --> 00:09:31.440 align:middle line:84%
Can you think of an example
where that actually happens?

00:09:31.440 --> 00:09:32.200 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:35.560 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: You could choose
x to be like the diagonal--

00:09:35.560 --> 00:09:42.760 align:middle line:84%
like all the values like, I
guess, pi I for I is in Fp.

00:09:42.760 --> 00:09:43.580 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:09:43.580 --> 00:09:48.050 align:middle line:90%
So here's an example.

00:09:48.050 --> 00:09:51.050 align:middle line:84%
So x is going to be
contained in A cross

00:09:51.050 --> 00:09:58.450 align:middle line:84%
A. X is the set of all
A comma A in A cross A.

00:09:58.450 --> 00:10:02.170 align:middle line:84%
And so then if I take
the projection, I guess,

00:10:02.170 --> 00:10:06.850 align:middle line:84%
in the direction minus
1 of x, I just get 0.

00:10:06.850 --> 00:10:08.810 align:middle line:90%
A minus A is always 0.

00:10:08.810 --> 00:10:14.270 align:middle line:84%
So this is extremely
small But in this case,

00:10:14.270 --> 00:10:17.530 align:middle line:84%
this x is quite a bit
smaller than the whole

00:10:17.530 --> 00:10:22.100 align:middle line:84%
A cross A. So let me make
a more precise question.

00:10:22.100 --> 00:10:25.050 align:middle line:90%


00:10:25.050 --> 00:10:32.670 align:middle line:84%
So let's say A has size N. And
x is a subset of A cross A,

00:10:32.670 --> 00:10:34.690 align:middle line:90%
and it's really quite big.

00:10:34.690 --> 00:10:37.250 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to say
x is bigger than--

00:10:37.250 --> 00:10:41.130 align:middle line:84%
well, we're going to call it for
now K inverse times N squared.

00:10:41.130 --> 00:10:49.580 align:middle line:84%
But then maybe K is order
of N to the 1 over 1,000.

00:10:49.580 --> 00:10:54.780 align:middle line:84%
So it's really a big
portion of A cross A.

00:10:54.780 --> 00:11:03.020 align:middle line:84%
And pi t of x is
like way smaller

00:11:03.020 --> 00:11:11.740 align:middle line:84%
than pi t of A cross A. We
could make that more precise

00:11:11.740 --> 00:11:12.880 align:middle line:90%
too, if we wanted to.

00:11:12.880 --> 00:11:16.460 align:middle line:90%


00:11:16.460 --> 00:11:18.820 align:middle line:84%
And that's the situation
we have in our attempt.

00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:22.340 align:middle line:90%


00:11:22.340 --> 00:11:25.180 align:middle line:90%
A is only a bit bigger than x.

00:11:25.180 --> 00:11:29.220 align:middle line:84%
And so let's say
the size of A is

00:11:29.220 --> 00:11:31.180 align:middle line:84%
N. It's just the
definition of N.

00:11:31.180 --> 00:11:35.020 align:middle line:84%
And then x would be bigger
than like p to the minus

00:11:35.020 --> 00:11:40.380 align:middle line:84%
a few epsilon size of A
cross A. So it's really

00:11:40.380 --> 00:11:41.890 align:middle line:90%
a good portion of that.

00:11:41.890 --> 00:11:50.110 align:middle line:90%


00:11:50.110 --> 00:11:54.430 align:middle line:84%
So could it still happen that
the size of the projection of x

00:11:54.430 --> 00:11:56.750 align:middle line:84%
is way smaller than the
size of the projection

00:11:56.750 --> 00:11:57.690 align:middle line:90%
of the whole thing?

00:11:57.690 --> 00:12:04.110 align:middle line:90%


00:12:04.110 --> 00:12:05.310 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: This is like--

00:12:05.310 --> 00:12:07.570 align:middle line:84%
can you pigeonhole
principle somehow,

00:12:07.570 --> 00:12:11.870 align:middle line:84%
like the fibers of the
projection of A cross A?

00:12:11.870 --> 00:12:13.387 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:12:13.387 --> 00:12:14.970 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: And then
if x is big enough,

00:12:14.970 --> 00:12:21.470 align:middle line:84%
you know it has to be at
least some nice number.

00:12:21.470 --> 00:12:22.333 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:12:22.333 --> 00:12:23.750 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: So the
suggestion is we

00:12:23.750 --> 00:12:28.370 align:middle line:84%
can look at all of the fibers
of the projection of A cross A,

00:12:28.370 --> 00:12:32.540 align:middle line:84%
and then we should pick x to
be the union of the big fibers.

00:12:32.540 --> 00:12:35.110 align:middle line:90%


00:12:35.110 --> 00:12:37.150 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:12:37.150 --> 00:12:38.070 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:12:38.070 --> 00:12:38.810 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:12:38.810 --> 00:12:40.960 align:middle line:84%
So in this enemy
scenario, there have

00:12:40.960 --> 00:12:44.040 align:middle line:84%
to be some very big fibers and
some much smaller fibers that

00:12:44.040 --> 00:12:46.980 align:middle line:84%
have to be kind different
from each other.

00:12:46.980 --> 00:12:47.480 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:12:47.480 --> 00:12:51.240 align:middle line:90%


00:12:51.240 --> 00:12:55.845 align:middle line:84%
But let's see if we can think of
an example where this happens.

00:12:55.845 --> 00:12:56.720 align:middle line:90%
What I should erase--

00:12:56.720 --> 00:13:07.200 align:middle line:90%


00:13:07.200 --> 00:13:10.680 align:middle line:90%
probably still have some space.

00:13:10.680 --> 00:13:15.060 align:middle line:84%
So I'm just going to
continue below the line here.

00:13:15.060 --> 00:13:21.680 align:middle line:90%


00:13:21.680 --> 00:13:23.880 align:middle line:84%
So first of all, can we
even think of an example

00:13:23.880 --> 00:13:29.560 align:middle line:84%
where the projection of x or of
something would be small at all?

00:13:29.560 --> 00:13:35.820 align:middle line:84%
So an example, maybe x could
be the numbers from 1 up to N

00:13:35.820 --> 00:13:41.130 align:middle line:84%
cross the numbers from 1
up to N. And then pi 1 of x

00:13:41.130 --> 00:13:44.010 align:middle line:90%
is pretty small.

00:13:44.010 --> 00:13:48.090 align:middle line:84%
It would be basically
integers from 1 up to 2N,

00:13:48.090 --> 00:13:49.400 align:middle line:90%
so this would be quite small.

00:13:49.400 --> 00:13:57.596 align:middle line:90%


00:13:57.596 --> 00:14:03.370 align:middle line:84%
So you could make this A. So
x would be all of A cross A.

00:14:03.370 --> 00:14:06.410 align:middle line:84%
Then the projection of A
cross A would be small.

00:14:06.410 --> 00:14:10.330 align:middle line:84%
But you could also inflate A
to make it bigger than that.

00:14:10.330 --> 00:14:15.090 align:middle line:84%
So we could take A to be
the integers from 1 up to N

00:14:15.090 --> 00:14:17.770 align:middle line:90%
union, A tilde.

00:14:17.770 --> 00:14:20.670 align:middle line:84%
Maybe this size of
A tilde is also N,

00:14:20.670 --> 00:14:22.860 align:middle line:84%
but A tilde is
unstructured or random.

00:14:22.860 --> 00:14:31.650 align:middle line:90%


00:14:31.650 --> 00:14:38.180 align:middle line:84%
So now if I take
pi 1 of A cross A,

00:14:38.180 --> 00:14:43.940 align:middle line:84%
it's at least as big as pi
1 of A tilde cross A tilde.

00:14:43.940 --> 00:14:46.980 align:middle line:84%
And A tilde has nothing to
do with the numbers from 1

00:14:46.980 --> 00:14:49.320 align:middle line:84%
up to N. I could build
some set where that's big.

00:14:49.320 --> 00:14:54.580 align:middle line:90%


00:14:54.580 --> 00:15:01.260 align:middle line:84%
But pi 1 of x is only
around N. So there could be

00:15:01.260 --> 00:15:02.930 align:middle line:90%
a big gap between these guys.

00:15:02.930 --> 00:15:08.740 align:middle line:90%


00:15:08.740 --> 00:15:12.140 align:middle line:90%
But this example is not so--

00:15:12.140 --> 00:15:14.320 align:middle line:84%
not such a problem
for our strategy.

00:15:14.320 --> 00:15:17.100 align:middle line:84%
Because in this example,
we just should have chosen

00:15:17.100 --> 00:15:20.500 align:middle line:90%
the set A smaller like A to B.

00:15:20.500 --> 00:15:22.000 align:middle line:90%
We could choose as we like.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.100 align:middle line:84%
We could choose a
smaller set A so

00:15:24.100 --> 00:15:27.820 align:middle line:84%
that A actually with the smaller
choice of A, just these guys, x

00:15:27.820 --> 00:15:31.840 align:middle line:84%
would be A cross A. And
then we would be happy.

00:15:31.840 --> 00:15:35.176 align:middle line:90%


00:15:35.176 --> 00:15:38.910 align:middle line:84%
So the key to the
proof of Bougain, Katz,

00:15:38.910 --> 00:15:41.350 align:middle line:84%
Tao is a theorem
from combinatorics

00:15:41.350 --> 00:15:43.850 align:middle line:84%
called the
Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers theorem.

00:15:43.850 --> 00:15:46.510 align:middle line:84%
And it says that this
example is pretty much

00:15:46.510 --> 00:15:50.150 align:middle line:84%
the only way that pi 1 of x
could be much smaller than pi1

00:15:50.150 --> 00:16:21.410 align:middle line:90%
of A cross A.

00:16:21.410 --> 00:16:24.310 align:middle line:84%
So, this is called the
Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers theorem.

00:16:24.310 --> 00:16:30.630 align:middle line:84%
And it's another of the central
tools in the toolbox of additive

00:16:30.630 --> 00:16:33.800 align:middle line:84%
combinatorics, along with the
Plünnecke-Ruzsa inequalities

00:16:33.800 --> 00:16:36.160 align:middle line:90%
that we talked about last time.

00:16:36.160 --> 00:16:37.020 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:16:37.020 --> 00:16:43.520 align:middle line:84%
So it says, if A and B are
contained in an abelian group

00:16:43.520 --> 00:16:52.080 align:middle line:84%
and they have size
at most, N. And I

00:16:52.080 --> 00:16:59.412 align:middle line:84%
have a subset of A cross
B, which is significant--

00:16:59.412 --> 00:17:02.400 align:middle line:90%
a significant fraction.

00:17:02.400 --> 00:17:07.000 align:middle line:84%
And the projection of this
subset in some direction

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:07.590 align:middle line:90%
is small.

00:17:07.590 --> 00:17:15.760 align:middle line:90%


00:17:15.760 --> 00:17:17.560 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:17:17.560 --> 00:17:20.160 align:middle line:84%
So, here, I want you
to imagine that K

00:17:20.160 --> 00:17:23.000 align:middle line:84%
is a lot smaller
than N. So, this

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:25.260 align:middle line:84%
is a big chunk of all
the pairs, A and B.

00:17:25.260 --> 00:17:28.060 align:middle line:84%
And the smallest this could
possibly be is around N,

00:17:28.060 --> 00:17:31.080 align:middle line:84%
because if you just
fix one element of B,

00:17:31.080 --> 00:17:33.560 align:middle line:84%
you'd have around N choices
for this element of A.

00:17:33.560 --> 00:17:35.960 align:middle line:84%
So that would already
give you around N here.

00:17:35.960 --> 00:17:39.960 align:middle line:84%
So, this is almost
as small as possible.

00:17:39.960 --> 00:17:44.640 align:middle line:84%
And then, the conclusion is,
it's not necessarily the case

00:17:44.640 --> 00:17:47.060 align:middle line:84%
that pi T of all of
A cross B is small.

00:17:47.060 --> 00:17:49.040 align:middle line:84%
We just saw a
counterexample to that.

00:17:49.040 --> 00:17:53.120 align:middle line:84%
But we could find
big pieces of A and B

00:17:53.120 --> 00:17:56.600 align:middle line:84%
so that the projection of
the big pieces is small.

00:17:56.600 --> 00:18:00.740 align:middle line:84%
So, then, there exists
A prime and B prime,

00:18:00.740 --> 00:18:07.360 align:middle line:84%
which are subsets of A and B.
A prime and A, B prime and B,

00:18:07.360 --> 00:18:13.500 align:middle line:84%
so that, I'll say, x prime is
defined to be A prime cross

00:18:13.500 --> 00:18:15.120 align:middle line:90%
B prime, intersect, x.

00:18:15.120 --> 00:18:21.920 align:middle line:84%
And x prime is still a
big fraction of N squared.

00:18:21.920 --> 00:18:26.840 align:middle line:84%
So, K to the minus some
constant power, times N squared.

00:18:26.840 --> 00:18:32.490 align:middle line:84%
And if I take pi T
of A prime cross B

00:18:32.490 --> 00:18:39.810 align:middle line:84%
prime, that is less than K
to some power times N. So,

00:18:39.810 --> 00:18:41.140 align:middle line:90%
this is small.

00:18:41.140 --> 00:18:48.010 align:middle line:90%


00:18:48.010 --> 00:18:53.280 align:middle line:84%
So in this example here,
where A was like this,

00:18:53.280 --> 00:18:56.050 align:middle line:84%
this part here would
be the A prime.

00:18:56.050 --> 00:18:58.250 align:middle line:90%
And it would be symmetric.

00:18:58.250 --> 00:19:00.070 align:middle line:84%
B prime and A prime
would both be this.

00:19:00.070 --> 00:19:06.490 align:middle line:90%


00:19:06.490 --> 00:19:08.650 align:middle line:84%
OK, take a moment to
digest that statement

00:19:08.650 --> 00:19:10.400 align:middle line:84%
and see if you have
questions or comments.

00:19:10.400 --> 00:19:14.450 align:middle line:90%


00:19:14.450 --> 00:19:15.914 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:15.914 --> 00:19:20.110 align:middle line:84%
So, we will prove this
probably starting later today,

00:19:20.110 --> 00:19:22.530 align:middle line:90%
but most of it next class.

00:19:22.530 --> 00:19:25.090 align:middle line:84%
But for the rest of
this class, we'll

00:19:25.090 --> 00:19:26.390 align:middle line:90%
explore why this is useful.

00:19:26.390 --> 00:19:29.840 align:middle line:84%
And in particular, we'll use it
to prove the projection theorem,

00:19:29.840 --> 00:19:30.340 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:19:30.340 --> 00:19:33.110 align:middle line:90%


00:19:33.110 --> 00:19:33.610 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:19:33.610 --> 00:19:59.540 align:middle line:90%


00:19:59.540 --> 00:20:00.160 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:20:00.160 --> 00:20:05.290 align:middle line:84%
So, let's do the proof of the
Bourgain-Katz-Tao projection

00:20:05.290 --> 00:20:05.790 align:middle line:90%
theorem.

00:20:05.790 --> 00:20:11.620 align:middle line:90%


00:20:11.620 --> 00:20:16.835 align:middle line:84%
So, let's say epsilon
is small, to be decided.

00:20:16.835 --> 00:20:18.960 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to prove,
there's some small epsilon

00:20:18.960 --> 00:20:20.260 align:middle line:90%
where this is true.

00:20:20.260 --> 00:20:25.020 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to write
C less than tilde, tilde

00:20:25.020 --> 00:20:31.150 align:middle line:84%
D. It means that C is less
than p to the big O of epsilon,

00:20:31.150 --> 00:20:35.390 align:middle line:90%
times D.

00:20:35.390 --> 00:20:37.374 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:37.374 --> 00:20:40.170 align:middle line:84%
And, now, we're going to do
a proof by contradiction.

00:20:40.170 --> 00:20:47.270 align:middle line:84%
So we can suppose pi T of
x is less than or equal

00:20:47.270 --> 00:20:55.630 align:middle line:84%
to p to the epsilon, times x to
the half, for all the T and D.

00:20:55.630 --> 00:20:56.750 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:56.750 --> 00:20:58.430 align:middle line:84%
Without loss of
generality, I can

00:20:58.430 --> 00:21:01.830 align:middle line:84%
suppose that 0 or infinity
are in my directions.

00:21:01.830 --> 00:21:08.190 align:middle line:84%
And I'll take A to be pi 0
of x union, pi infinity of x.

00:21:08.190 --> 00:21:13.790 align:middle line:84%
And so, now, I know that x
is a subset of A cross A.

00:21:13.790 --> 00:21:17.510 align:middle line:84%
I'll say, A, the
size of A could be N.

00:21:17.510 --> 00:21:20.630 align:middle line:84%
And that is tilde,
tilde, the square root

00:21:20.630 --> 00:21:24.210 align:middle line:84%
of x, up to some powers
of p to the epsilon.

00:21:24.210 --> 00:21:26.660 align:middle line:90%


00:21:26.660 --> 00:21:27.160 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:21:27.160 --> 00:21:32.960 align:middle line:84%
And, therefore, x is greater
tilde, tilde, N squared.

00:21:32.960 --> 00:21:39.320 align:middle line:84%
So x is a big fraction of
all of A cross N. Cool.

00:21:39.320 --> 00:21:46.200 align:middle line:84%
Next, I choose
some other T1 in D.

00:21:46.200 --> 00:21:58.800 align:middle line:84%
And I know that pi T1 of x
is less than tilde, tilde, N.

00:21:58.800 --> 00:22:03.360 align:middle line:84%
And so, once I know this, the
Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers theorem

00:22:03.360 --> 00:22:08.920 align:middle line:84%
tells me that this comes from a
product, A prime, A prime cross

00:22:08.920 --> 00:22:10.320 align:middle line:90%
B prime.

00:22:10.320 --> 00:22:19.040 align:middle line:84%
So, Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers says,
this A prime in A, B prime in B.

00:22:19.040 --> 00:22:23.250 align:middle line:84%
And x prime is the part of x
and its product, A prime cross B

00:22:23.250 --> 00:22:24.050 align:middle line:90%
prime.

00:22:24.050 --> 00:22:28.050 align:middle line:84%
So, first of all, x prime
is still quite substantial.

00:22:28.050 --> 00:22:33.580 align:middle line:84%
And pi T1 of A prime
cross B prime is small.

00:22:33.580 --> 00:22:37.570 align:middle line:90%


00:22:37.570 --> 00:22:41.850 align:middle line:84%
And this means, in other
words, that A prime plus T1 B

00:22:41.850 --> 00:22:43.400 align:middle line:90%
prime is small.

00:22:43.400 --> 00:22:56.170 align:middle line:90%


00:22:56.170 --> 00:22:58.360 align:middle line:90%
And this here is--

00:22:58.360 --> 00:23:02.810 align:middle line:90%


00:23:02.810 --> 00:23:08.470 align:middle line:84%
this information here is
strong in a helpful way.

00:23:08.470 --> 00:23:11.090 align:middle line:84%
It's stronger than
this, because, here, we

00:23:11.090 --> 00:23:13.910 align:middle line:84%
can use the Plunnecke-Ruzsa
inequalities.

00:23:13.910 --> 00:23:16.610 align:middle line:90%


00:23:16.610 --> 00:23:22.820 align:middle line:84%
So, once we know that A prime
plus T1 B prime is small,

00:23:22.820 --> 00:23:28.140 align:middle line:84%
then Plünnecke-Ruzsa
inequalities tell us that lots

00:23:28.140 --> 00:23:29.640 align:middle line:90%
of other things are small.

00:23:29.640 --> 00:23:35.340 align:middle line:84%
So, for example, A prime, plus
or minus A prime, is also small.

00:23:35.340 --> 00:23:39.740 align:middle line:84%
If I wanted to, I could
do a triple sum, A prime,

00:23:39.740 --> 00:23:44.620 align:middle line:84%
plus A prime, plus A prime,
is also small, dot, dot, dot.

00:23:44.620 --> 00:23:48.420 align:middle line:84%
You could do the
same with B prime.

00:23:48.420 --> 00:23:51.100 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:23:51.100 --> 00:23:56.940 align:middle line:84%
So, now, we see that A prime and
B prime have a lot of structure,

00:23:56.940 --> 00:23:58.038 align:middle line:90%
have a lot of structure.

00:23:58.038 --> 00:23:59.830 align:middle line:84%
And, actually, I'll
use the word, symmetry.

00:23:59.830 --> 00:24:03.140 align:middle line:90%


00:24:03.140 --> 00:24:03.760 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:24:03.760 --> 00:24:06.973 align:middle line:90%


00:24:06.973 --> 00:24:09.340 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:24:09.340 --> 00:24:10.900 align:middle line:84%
Actually, I'll
draw you a picture

00:24:10.900 --> 00:24:13.980 align:middle line:84%
in a minute of how
I visualize this,

00:24:13.980 --> 00:24:16.130 align:middle line:90%
and why I use the word symmetry.

00:24:16.130 --> 00:24:19.430 align:middle line:90%


00:24:19.430 --> 00:24:21.286 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:24:21.286 --> 00:24:22.120 align:middle line:90%
So, next.

00:24:22.120 --> 00:24:29.950 align:middle line:90%


00:24:29.950 --> 00:24:31.930 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, I have to make space.

00:24:31.930 --> 00:24:33.930 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to erase the
statement of the theorem.

00:24:33.930 --> 00:24:36.430 align:middle line:84%
We're going to try to prove
that one of the projections of x

00:24:36.430 --> 00:24:38.790 align:middle line:90%
is big.

00:24:38.790 --> 00:24:39.290 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:24:39.290 --> 00:24:47.870 align:middle line:90%


00:24:47.870 --> 00:24:48.690 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:24:48.690 --> 00:24:52.150 align:middle line:90%


00:24:52.150 --> 00:24:52.650 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:24:52.650 --> 00:24:54.950 align:middle line:84%
So, now, we have
a lemma that says,

00:24:54.950 --> 00:24:58.522 align:middle line:84%
if I have a subset y in
A prime cross B prime--

00:24:58.522 --> 00:25:00.730 align:middle line:84%
the subset we're going to
care about is just x prime.

00:25:00.730 --> 00:25:04.070 align:middle line:90%
But the lemma is more general.

00:25:04.070 --> 00:25:10.310 align:middle line:84%
And A prime and B prime
have these nice properties.

00:25:10.310 --> 00:25:12.410 align:middle line:90%
So, I'll just copy these two.

00:25:12.410 --> 00:25:17.270 align:middle line:90%


00:25:17.270 --> 00:25:21.410 align:middle line:84%
A prime plus T1
B prime is small.

00:25:21.410 --> 00:25:24.280 align:middle line:90%


00:25:24.280 --> 00:25:27.880 align:middle line:90%
A prime minus A prime is small.

00:25:27.880 --> 00:25:33.560 align:middle line:84%
And y itself is fairly
large, although I don't need

00:25:33.560 --> 00:25:36.680 align:middle line:90%
to write it in the statement.

00:25:36.680 --> 00:25:39.360 align:middle line:90%
Then.

00:25:39.360 --> 00:25:42.280 align:middle line:84%
pi T of y-- so this
is for any T. So,

00:25:42.280 --> 00:25:45.250 align:middle line:84%
T is just anybody in
Fp, different from T1.

00:25:45.250 --> 00:25:47.920 align:middle line:90%


00:25:47.920 --> 00:25:53.860 align:middle line:84%
This guy is bigger
than, tilde, tilde,

00:25:53.860 --> 00:26:01.280 align:middle line:84%
y over N squared, times pi
in a different direction,

00:26:01.280 --> 00:26:05.110 align:middle line:84%
T over T1, of A
prime cross A prime.

00:26:05.110 --> 00:26:13.200 align:middle line:90%


00:26:13.200 --> 00:26:18.210 align:middle line:84%
So, we have-- the
biggest y it could be is,

00:26:18.210 --> 00:26:20.830 align:middle line:84%
it could have size around
N squared, in which case

00:26:20.830 --> 00:26:23.890 align:middle line:90%
this would disappear.

00:26:23.890 --> 00:26:26.890 align:middle line:84%
And so, I said, if we have a
large subset of A prime cross B

00:26:26.890 --> 00:26:31.050 align:middle line:84%
prime, then the projection
of that large subset y

00:26:31.050 --> 00:26:33.770 align:middle line:84%
is bigger than the
projection and related

00:26:33.770 --> 00:26:37.970 align:middle line:84%
angle of a whole product,
A prime cross A prime.

00:26:37.970 --> 00:26:43.610 align:middle line:84%
This is good for us because we
can apply theorem 1 to this.

00:26:43.610 --> 00:26:51.290 align:middle line:84%
And, this inequality,
you're kind of ruling out

00:26:51.290 --> 00:26:52.590 align:middle line:90%
the enemy scenario.

00:26:52.590 --> 00:26:55.130 align:middle line:84%
We're ruling out the possibility
that there's a big chunk

00:26:55.130 --> 00:26:57.542 align:middle line:84%
of A prime cross B prime
that got compressed,

00:26:57.542 --> 00:26:59.000 align:middle line:84%
even though the
whole thing didn't.

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:02.730 align:middle line:90%


00:27:02.730 --> 00:27:03.850 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:03.850 --> 00:27:07.390 align:middle line:84%
Let me put over
here, some intuition.

00:27:07.390 --> 00:27:11.130 align:middle line:90%


00:27:11.130 --> 00:27:19.020 align:middle line:84%
So, my intuition is that A prime
cross B prime is very symmetric.

00:27:19.020 --> 00:27:21.920 align:middle line:84%
And so, let me draw an
exaggerated version.

00:27:21.920 --> 00:27:24.610 align:middle line:84%
Suppose that A prime cross B
prime does look like a lattice.

00:27:24.610 --> 00:27:31.020 align:middle line:90%


00:27:31.020 --> 00:27:37.180 align:middle line:84%
And inside of there, we
have some substantial but

00:27:37.180 --> 00:27:39.138 align:middle line:90%
unstructured set, y.

00:27:39.138 --> 00:27:43.440 align:middle line:90%


00:27:43.440 --> 00:27:48.380 align:middle line:84%
So, if there were some angle
where the projection of y

00:27:48.380 --> 00:27:51.940 align:middle line:84%
got compressed a lot, I
claim that compression

00:27:51.940 --> 00:27:55.340 align:middle line:84%
of the whole lattice should
get compressed a lot.

00:27:55.340 --> 00:27:56.220 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:27:56.220 --> 00:27:59.700 align:middle line:84%
Because the lattice
is symmetric.

00:27:59.700 --> 00:28:03.180 align:middle line:84%
So I can cover the lattice
by some translates of y.

00:28:03.180 --> 00:28:05.400 align:middle line:84%
And if each of those
gets compressed a lot,

00:28:05.400 --> 00:28:10.020 align:middle line:84%
then the whole lattice
should be compressed a lot.

00:28:10.020 --> 00:28:18.120 align:middle line:84%
So, we cover A prime cross B
prime by a few translates of y.

00:28:18.120 --> 00:28:23.140 align:middle line:90%


00:28:23.140 --> 00:28:27.860 align:middle line:84%
And then we would get that the
projection of the whole thing

00:28:27.860 --> 00:28:33.240 align:middle line:84%
should be bounded by a few
times, the projection of y.

00:28:33.240 --> 00:28:42.180 align:middle line:90%


00:28:42.180 --> 00:28:45.060 align:middle line:84%
So, now, let's carry
out this intuition.

00:28:45.060 --> 00:28:49.140 align:middle line:84%
We are going to cover
y, cover A prime,

00:28:49.140 --> 00:28:52.280 align:middle line:84%
cover something,
by translates of y.

00:28:52.280 --> 00:28:59.920 align:middle line:90%


00:28:59.920 --> 00:29:07.520 align:middle line:84%
So, let's consider
y plus T1, T2.

00:29:07.520 --> 00:29:09.500 align:middle line:84%
These are some
translates of y, a set

00:29:09.500 --> 00:29:17.190 align:middle line:84%
of these guys, where T1
is an A prime cross A

00:29:17.190 --> 00:29:19.430 align:middle line:90%
prime, minus A prime.

00:29:19.430 --> 00:29:27.410 align:middle line:84%
And T2 is in this slightly
weird-looking thing there.

00:29:27.410 --> 00:29:33.070 align:middle line:90%


00:29:33.070 --> 00:29:37.830 align:middle line:84%
And so, these are a
bunch of translates of y.

00:29:37.830 --> 00:29:46.430 align:middle line:84%
And these translates of y
cover somebody a lot of times.

00:29:46.430 --> 00:29:54.033 align:middle line:90%
So, for every y1, y2--

00:29:54.033 --> 00:29:54.950 align:middle line:90%
let me do it this way.

00:29:54.950 --> 00:29:59.470 align:middle line:84%
For every A1, A2,
and A prime cross

00:29:59.470 --> 00:30:05.750 align:middle line:84%
A prime, and for
every y1, y2, and y,

00:30:05.750 --> 00:30:16.280 align:middle line:84%
there is a unique T1, T2,
which is in this list,

00:30:16.280 --> 00:30:24.600 align:middle line:84%
so that y1, y2, plus
T1, T2, is a1, a2.

00:30:24.600 --> 00:30:29.640 align:middle line:84%
So this is easier to prove
than it is to write down.

00:30:29.640 --> 00:30:31.720 align:middle line:90%
Just solve for T1.

00:30:31.720 --> 00:30:36.040 align:middle line:90%
T1 must be a1 minus Y1.

00:30:36.040 --> 00:30:39.340 align:middle line:84%
And these guys both
live in A prime.

00:30:39.340 --> 00:30:43.040 align:middle line:90%
So, T1 is in there.

00:30:43.040 --> 00:30:50.240 align:middle line:90%
And, ah, wait.

00:30:50.240 --> 00:30:51.100 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, sorry.

00:30:51.100 --> 00:30:55.380 align:middle line:84%
So this is going to have to
be negative 1 over T1a prime.

00:30:55.380 --> 00:30:58.010 align:middle line:90%
OK, now, how does y2 work?

00:30:58.010 --> 00:31:01.960 align:middle line:90%


00:31:01.960 --> 00:31:05.640 align:middle line:84%
So, T2 is going
to be a2 minus y2.

00:31:05.640 --> 00:31:13.450 align:middle line:90%
And the a2 lives in B prime.

00:31:13.450 --> 00:31:41.020 align:middle line:90%


00:31:41.020 --> 00:31:41.520 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:31:41.520 --> 00:31:44.490 align:middle line:90%


00:31:44.490 --> 00:31:47.570 align:middle line:90%
So, the a2 lives here.

00:31:47.570 --> 00:31:52.070 align:middle line:90%
And the y2 lives here.

00:31:52.070 --> 00:31:54.910 align:middle line:84%
So the difference lives
here, where it's supposed to.

00:31:54.910 --> 00:32:06.300 align:middle line:90%


00:32:06.300 --> 00:32:14.780 align:middle line:84%
So, these translates of
y cover A prime cross

00:32:14.780 --> 00:32:17.860 align:middle line:90%
negative 1 over T1a prime.

00:32:17.860 --> 00:32:22.540 align:middle line:90%
They cover it y times.

00:32:22.540 --> 00:32:24.560 align:middle line:84%
They cover each
point in here y times

00:32:24.560 --> 00:32:30.220 align:middle line:84%
because, for each point
in here, I have norm of y,

00:32:30.220 --> 00:32:33.060 align:middle line:84%
cardinality of y
choices for this guy.

00:32:33.060 --> 00:32:37.300 align:middle line:84%
And then there's
one in translation,

00:32:37.300 --> 00:32:39.480 align:middle line:84%
a set of translations
that lands here.

00:32:39.480 --> 00:32:43.260 align:middle line:90%


00:32:43.260 --> 00:32:45.290 align:middle line:90%
Does this sentence make sense?

00:32:45.290 --> 00:32:49.580 align:middle line:90%


00:32:49.580 --> 00:32:53.100 align:middle line:84%
So we have rigged it, that we've
taken a bunch of translations

00:32:53.100 --> 00:32:54.820 align:middle line:90%
of this set, y.

00:32:54.820 --> 00:32:59.100 align:middle line:84%
And we have covered a
nice product many times.

00:32:59.100 --> 00:33:01.780 align:middle line:84%
And the product, we actually
could have arranged the product

00:33:01.780 --> 00:33:03.020 align:middle line:90%
to be A prime cross B prime.

00:33:03.020 --> 00:33:05.270 align:middle line:84%
That would have been a little
easier than what we did.

00:33:05.270 --> 00:33:07.950 align:middle line:84%
But we have arranged that the
product that we've covered

00:33:07.950 --> 00:33:11.697 align:middle line:84%
is A prime cross a
dilation of A prime.

00:33:11.697 --> 00:33:13.530 align:middle line:84%
And that's a little bit
better, technically,

00:33:13.530 --> 00:33:15.410 align:middle line:84%
because it's going to
be closer to theorem 1.

00:33:15.410 --> 00:33:18.790 align:middle line:90%


00:33:18.790 --> 00:33:24.750 align:middle line:84%
Now, notice that this guy
is small by hypothesis.

00:33:24.750 --> 00:33:28.370 align:middle line:90%
And this set here is also small.

00:33:28.370 --> 00:33:32.950 align:middle line:90%
This is just a dilate of this.

00:33:32.950 --> 00:33:35.310 align:middle line:90%
So these sets are small.

00:33:35.310 --> 00:33:37.870 align:middle line:84%
So we took a few
translations of y.

00:33:37.870 --> 00:33:41.950 align:middle line:84%
And we covered this
product many times.

00:33:41.950 --> 00:33:43.718 align:middle line:84%
And that means that,
at least, typically,

00:33:43.718 --> 00:33:46.260 align:middle line:84%
each of these translations was
covering a lot of the product.

00:33:46.260 --> 00:33:49.590 align:middle line:90%


00:33:49.590 --> 00:33:53.750 align:middle line:90%
So that matches this intuition.

00:33:53.750 --> 00:34:01.430 align:middle line:84%
So, then, we can say that pi
T of A prime cross minus 1

00:34:01.430 --> 00:34:09.719 align:middle line:84%
over T, T1a prime, that
guy is bounded by--

00:34:09.719 --> 00:34:18.639 align:middle line:84%
OK, so we're going to take
A prime minus A prime,

00:34:18.639 --> 00:34:25.000 align:middle line:90%
times A prime plus T1 B prime.

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:28.280 align:middle line:84%
This is how many
copies of y we took.

00:34:28.280 --> 00:34:30.380 align:middle line:84%
For each one of them,
we have a projection.

00:34:30.380 --> 00:34:33.960 align:middle line:90%
So that has the size, pi T of y.

00:34:33.960 --> 00:34:37.199 align:middle line:84%
And after doing that, we've
covered every point here

00:34:37.199 --> 00:34:38.260 align:middle line:90%
y times.

00:34:38.260 --> 00:34:39.540 align:middle line:90%
So we have this guy.

00:34:39.540 --> 00:34:49.560 align:middle line:90%


00:34:49.560 --> 00:34:52.460 align:middle line:84%
These are hypothesis
bounded by N.

00:34:52.460 --> 00:34:58.500 align:middle line:84%
So this is N squared
over y, pi T of y.

00:34:58.500 --> 00:35:01.090 align:middle line:90%


00:35:01.090 --> 00:35:03.750 align:middle line:84%
And that's basically
our final inequality.

00:35:03.750 --> 00:35:07.090 align:middle line:90%
Put the pi T of y by itself.

00:35:07.090 --> 00:35:13.530 align:middle line:84%
Pi T of y is greater, tilde,
tilde, y over N squared, times

00:35:13.530 --> 00:35:15.250 align:middle line:84%
the size of this
thingy, which is

00:35:15.250 --> 00:35:22.245 align:middle line:84%
equivalent to pi negative T
over T1, A prime cross A prime.

00:35:22.245 --> 00:35:55.970 align:middle line:90%


00:35:55.970 --> 00:35:57.750 align:middle line:90%
OK, take a moment with that.

00:35:57.750 --> 00:36:22.940 align:middle line:90%


00:36:22.940 --> 00:36:23.440 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:36:23.440 --> 00:36:27.940 align:middle line:90%


00:36:27.940 --> 00:36:30.990 align:middle line:84%
So, now, let's finish the
proof of the BKT theorem.

00:36:30.990 --> 00:36:43.420 align:middle line:90%


00:36:43.420 --> 00:36:44.200 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:36:44.200 --> 00:36:50.540 align:middle line:90%


00:36:50.540 --> 00:36:54.260 align:middle line:84%
So, we would like to estimate
the maximum T in our direction

00:36:54.260 --> 00:36:58.150 align:middle line:90%
set of pi T of x.

00:36:58.150 --> 00:37:01.990 align:middle line:84%
That's at least the
maximum T in our direction

00:37:01.990 --> 00:37:06.030 align:middle line:90%
set of pi T of x prime.

00:37:06.030 --> 00:37:07.490 align:middle line:84%
We're following
up from over here.

00:37:07.490 --> 00:37:10.960 align:middle line:84%
And here's x prime, which is
a big chunk of A prime cross

00:37:10.960 --> 00:37:11.460 align:middle line:90%
B prime.

00:37:11.460 --> 00:37:14.190 align:middle line:90%


00:37:14.190 --> 00:37:19.270 align:middle line:90%
And now, we can apply our lemma.

00:37:19.270 --> 00:37:23.990 align:middle line:84%
The lemma says, that
is at least as big

00:37:23.990 --> 00:37:29.270 align:middle line:84%
as the maximum T in our
direction set, x prime over N

00:37:29.270 --> 00:37:30.350 align:middle line:90%
squared.

00:37:30.350 --> 00:37:36.500 align:middle line:84%
And then we have pi negative T
over T1, A prime cross A prime.

00:37:36.500 --> 00:37:41.950 align:middle line:90%


00:37:41.950 --> 00:37:44.590 align:middle line:84%
Now, x prime, we
already determined,

00:37:44.590 --> 00:37:46.050 align:middle line:90%
has a size of about N squared.

00:37:46.050 --> 00:37:48.990 align:middle line:90%
So this factor disappears.

00:37:48.990 --> 00:37:51.550 align:middle line:84%
And now, we are
looking at projections

00:37:51.550 --> 00:37:55.290 align:middle line:84%
in many different directions
of A prime cross A prime.

00:37:55.290 --> 00:37:59.120 align:middle line:84%
That's exactly the thing
that theorem 1 told us about.

00:37:59.120 --> 00:38:06.584 align:middle line:84%
So, by theorem 1, this is
now greater [INAUDIBLE]

00:38:06.584 --> 00:38:11.520 align:middle line:90%
N times p to the epsilon 1.

00:38:11.520 --> 00:38:13.920 align:middle line:90%
And that's the proof.

00:38:13.920 --> 00:38:16.360 align:middle line:84%
So, one of these is
significantly bigger

00:38:16.360 --> 00:38:22.660 align:middle line:84%
than the square root of x
times p to the epsilon 1.

00:38:22.660 --> 00:38:50.340 align:middle line:90%


00:38:50.340 --> 00:38:50.840 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:38:50.840 --> 00:39:01.080 align:middle line:90%


00:39:01.080 --> 00:39:06.120 align:middle line:84%
Let me put up on here a
little summary of what we did.

00:39:06.120 --> 00:39:13.400 align:middle line:84%
And then I'll let you look down
from above at the whole thing.

00:39:13.400 --> 00:39:19.760 align:middle line:84%
So, we're trying to get from
theorem 1 to theorem BKT.

00:39:19.760 --> 00:39:25.680 align:middle line:84%
And the enemy was that we
have a set x in A cross A,

00:39:25.680 --> 00:39:29.760 align:middle line:84%
where x is around the
same size as A cross A.

00:39:29.760 --> 00:39:33.880 align:middle line:84%
But the size of
the projection of x

00:39:33.880 --> 00:39:38.340 align:middle line:84%
is much smaller than the size
of the projection of A cross.

00:39:38.340 --> 00:39:41.480 align:middle line:90%
A. That's our enemy.

00:39:41.480 --> 00:39:44.960 align:middle line:84%
And we learned two pieces
of wisdom about this enemy,

00:39:44.960 --> 00:39:49.240 align:middle line:84%
one in the BSG theorem,
and one in the lemma.

00:39:49.240 --> 00:39:55.190 align:middle line:84%
So, wisdom one, in
the enemy situation,

00:39:55.190 --> 00:39:59.290 align:middle line:90%
x lives in a smaller product.

00:39:59.290 --> 00:40:01.560 align:middle line:84%
And the projection of
the smaller product--

00:40:01.560 --> 00:40:04.290 align:middle line:90%


00:40:04.290 --> 00:40:07.300 align:middle line:84%
the projection of
the smaller product,

00:40:07.300 --> 00:40:08.550 align:middle line:90%
well, it doesn't live in that.

00:40:08.550 --> 00:40:10.170 align:middle line:90%
But it has a--

00:40:10.170 --> 00:40:13.530 align:middle line:84%
so the enemy situation
implies that x,

00:40:13.530 --> 00:40:17.310 align:middle line:84%
intersected with a smaller
product, is about the same as x.

00:40:17.310 --> 00:40:19.630 align:middle line:84%
So, a good chunk of x
lives in a smaller product.

00:40:19.630 --> 00:40:22.410 align:middle line:84%
And the projection of
the smaller product

00:40:22.410 --> 00:40:24.750 align:middle line:84%
is about the same as
the projection of x.

00:40:24.750 --> 00:40:27.930 align:middle line:90%


00:40:27.930 --> 00:40:30.810 align:middle line:90%
Then we look at that situation.

00:40:30.810 --> 00:40:33.330 align:middle line:84%
And the second
piece of wisdom was

00:40:33.330 --> 00:40:39.040 align:middle line:84%
that, if the projection of a
smaller product, of a product--

00:40:39.040 --> 00:40:42.690 align:middle line:90%


00:40:42.690 --> 00:40:50.360 align:middle line:84%
if this is small, so if this is
around the smallest it could be,

00:40:50.360 --> 00:40:54.100 align:middle line:84%
it would be one of the
factors for one T1.

00:40:54.100 --> 00:40:57.660 align:middle line:84%
Then this product
becomes very symmetrical.

00:40:57.660 --> 00:41:02.220 align:middle line:84%
And then the conclusion is,
for any subset, x prime,

00:41:02.220 --> 00:41:08.940 align:middle line:84%
in this thing, which
is substantial,

00:41:08.940 --> 00:41:12.380 align:middle line:84%
then the projection
of the subset

00:41:12.380 --> 00:41:15.795 align:middle line:84%
actually is around the
same as the projection

00:41:15.795 --> 00:41:16.670 align:middle line:90%
of the whole product.

00:41:16.670 --> 00:41:20.020 align:middle line:90%


00:41:20.020 --> 00:41:23.860 align:middle line:84%
So the enemy situation
can only really happen

00:41:23.860 --> 00:41:28.180 align:middle line:84%
because x was mostly in
a smaller product that

00:41:28.180 --> 00:41:30.820 align:middle line:90%
had a small projection.

00:41:30.820 --> 00:41:33.940 align:middle line:84%
And this situation
is very symmetrical.

00:41:33.940 --> 00:41:37.780 align:middle line:84%
So if a smaller product has
one small projection, then when

00:41:37.780 --> 00:41:42.460 align:middle line:84%
you project it in other
angles, then the projection

00:41:42.460 --> 00:41:44.895 align:middle line:84%
of a big piece of it
can't be way smaller

00:41:44.895 --> 00:41:46.520 align:middle line:84%
than the projection
of the whole thing.

00:41:46.520 --> 00:41:49.630 align:middle line:90%


00:41:49.630 --> 00:41:51.230 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:41:51.230 --> 00:41:54.430 align:middle line:84%
So, the whole story
is on these boards.

00:41:54.430 --> 00:41:56.770 align:middle line:84%
Take a couple of
moments to look it over.

00:41:56.770 --> 00:41:59.750 align:middle line:90%


00:41:59.750 --> 00:42:00.870 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:42:00.870 --> 00:42:01.830 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Professor?

00:42:01.830 --> 00:42:07.674 align:middle line:84%
So, should it be the case that
the A prime there depends on T?

00:42:07.674 --> 00:42:10.950 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: OK, so
the question is

00:42:10.950 --> 00:42:16.470 align:middle line:84%
whether A prime
depends on T. So,

00:42:16.470 --> 00:42:20.390 align:middle line:84%
let's see where
A prime appeared.

00:42:20.390 --> 00:42:25.550 align:middle line:84%
So we have our set with
many small projections.

00:42:25.550 --> 00:42:28.510 align:middle line:90%
And, OK.

00:42:28.510 --> 00:42:32.550 align:middle line:84%
And then, in particular,
the T1 projection is small.

00:42:32.550 --> 00:42:34.710 align:middle line:84%
And so, the
Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers theorem

00:42:34.710 --> 00:42:37.350 align:middle line:84%
says there's A prime
in A and B prime in B,

00:42:37.350 --> 00:42:42.230 align:middle line:84%
so that the T1 projection of A
prime cross B prime is small.

00:42:42.230 --> 00:42:46.030 align:middle line:90%
And this A prime depends on T1.

00:42:46.030 --> 00:42:50.180 align:middle line:84%
Now, later, we're going to look
at pi T of x for other T's.

00:42:50.180 --> 00:42:52.760 align:middle line:90%


00:42:52.760 --> 00:42:56.668 align:middle line:84%
One could, I guess, apply
Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers again

00:42:56.668 --> 00:42:57.460 align:middle line:90%
to those other T's.

00:42:57.460 --> 00:42:59.043 align:middle line:84%
But that's not what
we're going to do.

00:42:59.043 --> 00:43:02.193 align:middle line:84%
We use T1 to find A
prime and B prime.

00:43:02.193 --> 00:43:04.860 align:middle line:84%
And then we're going to run with
these same A prime and B prime,

00:43:04.860 --> 00:43:08.000 align:middle line:90%
even when we look at other T's.

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:09.840 align:middle line:90%
What did we learn?

00:43:09.840 --> 00:43:14.760 align:middle line:84%
Once we have this one small
projection, we learned--

00:43:14.760 --> 00:43:17.940 align:middle line:84%
Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers
told us this.

00:43:17.940 --> 00:43:19.820 align:middle line:84%
And then we learned from
it some other stuff.

00:43:19.820 --> 00:43:21.590 align:middle line:84%
So, what we actually
used is this.

00:43:21.590 --> 00:43:24.960 align:middle line:90%


00:43:24.960 --> 00:43:27.300 align:middle line:90%
So, then, we used this stack.

00:43:27.300 --> 00:43:29.920 align:middle line:84%
So this is telling us
that A prime cross B

00:43:29.920 --> 00:43:31.425 align:middle line:90%
prime is quite symmetrical.

00:43:31.425 --> 00:43:33.300 align:middle line:84%
And that's what's helpful
in the second part.

00:43:33.300 --> 00:43:34.060 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: OK, cool.

00:43:34.060 --> 00:43:34.560 align:middle line:90%
Thanks.

00:43:34.560 --> 00:43:38.353 align:middle line:90%


00:43:38.353 --> 00:43:39.020 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Good.

00:43:39.020 --> 00:43:40.187 align:middle line:90%
Other questions or comments?

00:43:40.187 --> 00:44:00.220 align:middle line:90%


00:44:00.220 --> 00:44:04.410 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Why don't we
know that A itself is also

00:44:04.410 --> 00:44:05.463 align:middle line:90%
kind of symmetrical?

00:44:05.463 --> 00:44:08.093 align:middle line:90%


00:44:08.093 --> 00:44:10.010 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, the
question is, why don't we

00:44:10.010 --> 00:44:13.050 align:middle line:84%
know that A itself is
also kind of symmetrical?

00:44:13.050 --> 00:44:16.450 align:middle line:84%
That might depend on exactly
what we mean by symmetrical.

00:44:16.450 --> 00:44:19.890 align:middle line:84%
But an important
thing, an important way

00:44:19.890 --> 00:44:25.730 align:middle line:84%
that A prime is better than
A is that, at this moment,

00:44:25.730 --> 00:44:28.490 align:middle line:90%
A prime minus A prime is small.

00:44:28.490 --> 00:44:33.530 align:middle line:84%
And we didn't know that about
A. You can think of A prime

00:44:33.530 --> 00:44:36.930 align:middle line:84%
as being A prime
plus some garbage.

00:44:36.930 --> 00:44:40.120 align:middle line:84%
And the garbage minus
garbage is not small.

00:44:40.120 --> 00:44:54.540 align:middle line:90%


00:44:54.540 --> 00:45:00.020 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So, [INAUDIBLE]
epsilon is different between

00:45:00.020 --> 00:45:05.300 align:middle line:84%
the two because of the A
prime plus minus A prime has--

00:45:05.300 --> 00:45:08.380 align:middle line:84%
there's a hidden
factor there, right?

00:45:08.380 --> 00:45:11.900 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yes, A prime
plus, minus, A prime.

00:45:11.900 --> 00:45:13.420 align:middle line:84%
Here, there's a
hidden factor, which

00:45:13.420 --> 00:45:15.412 align:middle line:90%
is p to the order of epsilon.

00:45:15.412 --> 00:45:16.120 align:middle line:90%
And you're right.

00:45:16.120 --> 00:45:17.700 align:middle line:84%
It's very important
that the epsilon

00:45:17.700 --> 00:45:19.330 align:middle line:84%
is different between
the two theorems.

00:45:19.330 --> 00:45:21.900 align:middle line:90%


00:45:21.900 --> 00:45:25.500 align:middle line:84%
So, epsilon 1 is the
epsilon in theorem 1, which

00:45:25.500 --> 00:45:27.300 align:middle line:84%
was already kind
of small, if we had

00:45:27.300 --> 00:45:29.660 align:middle line:90%
unwound the proof of theorem 1.

00:45:29.660 --> 00:45:33.500 align:middle line:84%
And then, in theorem
BKT, there's an epsilon.

00:45:33.500 --> 00:45:37.820 align:middle line:84%
And epsilon in BKT is way
smaller than the epsilon 1.

00:45:37.820 --> 00:45:40.980 align:middle line:84%
And the reason we
need that is, OK, we

00:45:40.980 --> 00:45:44.350 align:middle line:84%
started with this, where we have
a factor of p to the epsilon.

00:45:44.350 --> 00:45:46.770 align:middle line:90%
Then we did some stuff.

00:45:46.770 --> 00:45:49.030 align:middle line:90%
Most important stuff is BSG.

00:45:49.030 --> 00:45:51.870 align:middle line:90%
So, BSG, we'll lose--

00:45:51.870 --> 00:45:54.630 align:middle line:84%
there'll be a factor
of 10 epsilon here

00:45:54.630 --> 00:45:57.310 align:middle line:84%
that comes out of the proof
of Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers.

00:45:57.310 --> 00:45:59.270 align:middle line:84%
So, here, these things
will be something

00:45:59.270 --> 00:46:02.510 align:middle line:84%
like p to the 10 epsilon,
if you did them carefully.

00:46:02.510 --> 00:46:03.670 align:middle line:90%
And then you go along.

00:46:03.670 --> 00:46:05.670 align:middle line:90%
And we're following our proof.

00:46:05.670 --> 00:46:09.767 align:middle line:84%
So, here, we did a
little bit more work

00:46:09.767 --> 00:46:10.850 align:middle line:90%
in the proof of the lemma.

00:46:10.850 --> 00:46:16.830 align:middle line:84%
So, this is hiding a
p of 10 or 20 epsilon.

00:46:16.830 --> 00:46:19.510 align:middle line:84%
But, here, we have a gain
of p to the epsilon 1.

00:46:19.510 --> 00:46:22.430 align:middle line:84%
So, the p to the epsilon
1 needs to dominate the p

00:46:22.430 --> 00:46:24.670 align:middle line:84%
to the 20 epsilon that
we lost at various steps

00:46:24.670 --> 00:46:26.310 align:middle line:90%
in this process.

00:46:26.310 --> 00:46:32.350 align:middle line:84%
So, epsilon should be 1/20
of the size of epsilon 1.

00:46:32.350 --> 00:46:35.830 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so we have to do a whole
sequence of clever things

00:46:35.830 --> 00:46:37.890 align:middle line:84%
to prove
Bourgain-Katz-Tao theorem.

00:46:37.890 --> 00:46:39.590 align:middle line:84%
And each time we do
something clever,

00:46:39.590 --> 00:46:42.000 align:middle line:84%
epsilon gets smaller
by a factor of 10,

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:45.490 align:middle line:84%
until we're so clever that we
really can't see the epsilon.

00:46:45.490 --> 00:46:52.640 align:middle line:90%


00:46:52.640 --> 00:46:53.200 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:46:53.200 --> 00:46:55.000 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Is there a
conjectured boundary

00:46:55.000 --> 00:46:59.090 align:middle line:84%
for what the largest
possible epsilon could be?

00:46:59.090 --> 00:47:00.782 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Ah, that's
a great question.

00:47:00.782 --> 00:47:02.240 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so, the
question is, is there

00:47:02.240 --> 00:47:04.430 align:middle line:84%
a conjectured bound
about the right epsilon?

00:47:04.430 --> 00:47:07.960 align:middle line:90%


00:47:07.960 --> 00:47:08.840 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:47:08.840 --> 00:47:10.480 align:middle line:90%
So, yes.

00:47:10.480 --> 00:47:12.680 align:middle line:84%
So, the conjecture, so
we're working right now

00:47:12.680 --> 00:47:14.000 align:middle line:90%
over finite fields.

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:17.760 align:middle line:84%
And the conjecture is that
the worst case is a lattice.

00:47:17.760 --> 00:47:19.497 align:middle line:90%
And we wrote it down.

00:47:19.497 --> 00:47:20.580 align:middle line:90%
Let's write it down again.

00:47:20.580 --> 00:47:22.830 align:middle line:84%
But we wrote it down at the
beginning of the course.

00:47:22.830 --> 00:47:25.680 align:middle line:90%


00:47:25.680 --> 00:47:29.000 align:middle line:90%
So I think we're moving on.

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:30.020 align:middle line:90%
I'll put it here.

00:47:30.020 --> 00:47:32.960 align:middle line:90%


00:47:32.960 --> 00:47:41.050 align:middle line:84%
So, suppose we have x, which
is a subset of Fp squared.

00:47:41.050 --> 00:47:49.450 align:middle line:84%
And then we're going to take the
maximum t and D of pi t of x.

00:47:49.450 --> 00:47:51.730 align:middle line:90%
And this is bigger than--

00:47:51.730 --> 00:47:55.160 align:middle line:84%
I think it was D to
the 1/2, x to the 1/2.

00:47:55.160 --> 00:48:03.250 align:middle line:90%


00:48:03.250 --> 00:48:05.330 align:middle line:84%
Maybe you should check it
I don't remember these.

00:48:05.330 --> 00:48:07.690 align:middle line:84%
I don't quite remember this
off the top of my head.

00:48:07.690 --> 00:48:10.770 align:middle line:90%
So, I think.

00:48:10.770 --> 00:48:13.450 align:middle line:84%
And the way to remember
it is that the example

00:48:13.450 --> 00:48:15.060 align:middle line:90%
is that x is a lattice.

00:48:15.060 --> 00:48:17.970 align:middle line:90%


00:48:17.970 --> 00:48:26.850 align:middle line:84%
And then D is the set of
rational numbers of small slope.

00:48:26.850 --> 00:48:27.882 align:middle line:90%
That was the case with--

00:48:27.882 --> 00:48:30.590 align:middle line:84%
the case that we've seen so far,
where the projections are small.

00:48:30.590 --> 00:48:32.850 align:middle line:84%
So if you compute with this, you
can check whether this is true

00:48:32.850 --> 00:48:35.010 align:middle line:84%
or whether it needs to
be modified a little bit.

00:48:35.010 --> 00:48:37.500 align:middle line:84%
And then, if you rewrite
it in the language of BKT,

00:48:37.500 --> 00:48:41.260 align:middle line:84%
it gives you an exact
formula for epsilon.

00:48:41.260 --> 00:48:45.420 align:middle line:84%
And that is a wide-open
problem over FP.

00:48:45.420 --> 00:48:47.820 align:middle line:84%
But the version over
r has been proven.

00:48:47.820 --> 00:48:53.220 align:middle line:84%
And I'll try, at least,
to say at least some

00:48:53.220 --> 00:48:57.300 align:middle line:84%
of the main ideas of
the proof in the class.

00:48:57.300 --> 00:49:02.120 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, OK.

00:49:02.120 --> 00:49:07.040 align:middle line:90%


00:49:07.040 --> 00:49:11.900 align:middle line:84%
So, the ideas that we've just
been talking about, going

00:49:11.900 --> 00:49:14.780 align:middle line:84%
back and forth between whether a
projection of the whole product

00:49:14.780 --> 00:49:17.740 align:middle line:84%
is small, whether a projection
of a big chunk of the product

00:49:17.740 --> 00:49:21.720 align:middle line:84%
is small, that is a theme
in additive combinatorics.

00:49:21.720 --> 00:49:25.060 align:middle line:84%
And I want to describe to you
some of the other key words

00:49:25.060 --> 00:49:28.780 align:middle line:84%
and ideas behind that theme
to flesh out the lecture

00:49:28.780 --> 00:49:31.250 align:middle line:84%
and see how it fits
in, in general.

00:49:31.250 --> 00:49:35.850 align:middle line:90%


00:49:35.850 --> 00:49:36.350 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:49:36.350 --> 00:49:54.590 align:middle line:90%


00:49:54.590 --> 00:49:56.470 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:49:56.470 --> 00:50:02.590 align:middle line:84%
So, this section is
called additive energy

00:50:02.590 --> 00:50:09.070 align:middle line:84%
versus the size of
A plus B. So, these

00:50:09.070 --> 00:50:11.470 align:middle line:84%
are two points of
view about measuring

00:50:11.470 --> 00:50:15.510 align:middle line:84%
the additive structure involved
when you add numbers in A

00:50:15.510 --> 00:50:17.310 align:middle line:90%
to numbers in B.

00:50:17.310 --> 00:50:18.490 align:middle line:90%
This one, we've already met.

00:50:18.490 --> 00:50:21.550 align:middle line:84%
Let me tell you what
additive energy is.

00:50:21.550 --> 00:50:26.590 align:middle line:84%
So, the definition, if
A and B are contained

00:50:26.590 --> 00:50:32.470 align:middle line:84%
in an abelian group,
the energy of AB

00:50:32.470 --> 00:50:35.790 align:middle line:90%
is the number of quadruples.

00:50:35.790 --> 00:50:42.430 align:middle line:84%
A1 and A2 are in A.
B1 and B2 are in B,

00:50:42.430 --> 00:50:47.160 align:middle line:84%
so that A1 plus B1 is
equal to A2 plus B2.

00:50:47.160 --> 00:50:54.230 align:middle line:90%


00:50:54.230 --> 00:50:56.150 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:50:56.150 --> 00:50:58.050 align:middle line:84%
So, if you add
numbers from A and B,

00:50:58.050 --> 00:50:59.890 align:middle line:90%
how many coincidences are there?

00:50:59.890 --> 00:51:04.110 align:middle line:84%
Does it frequently happen
that you get the same number?

00:51:04.110 --> 00:51:06.110 align:middle line:84%
So, another way of
thinking about it

00:51:06.110 --> 00:51:11.190 align:middle line:84%
is we could say, r, AB of z, so
the number of representations

00:51:11.190 --> 00:51:15.750 align:middle line:84%
of z as a sum of somebody
in A and somebody in B.

00:51:15.750 --> 00:51:25.990 align:middle line:84%
So this is the number of
AB, so that A plus B is--

00:51:25.990 --> 00:51:33.320 align:middle line:84%
and the additive energy, AB, is
also equal to the sum over z,

00:51:33.320 --> 00:51:36.670 align:middle line:90%
rAB of z, squared.

00:51:36.670 --> 00:51:40.080 align:middle line:90%


00:51:40.080 --> 00:51:41.640 align:middle line:84%
So if this is large,
it means there

00:51:41.640 --> 00:51:44.320 align:middle line:84%
are a lot of numbers
that can be written as A

00:51:44.320 --> 00:51:46.240 align:middle line:90%
plus B in many different ways.

00:51:46.240 --> 00:51:48.060 align:middle line:84%
There are many
additive coincidences.

00:51:48.060 --> 00:51:54.480 align:middle line:90%


00:51:54.480 --> 00:52:00.280 align:middle line:84%
So, for reference, if
A and B both have size,

00:52:00.280 --> 00:52:04.080 align:middle line:84%
N, then let's
think about how big

00:52:04.080 --> 00:52:07.280 align:middle line:84%
or how small the
additive energy could be.

00:52:07.280 --> 00:52:10.360 align:middle line:90%
It's at least N squared.

00:52:10.360 --> 00:52:12.320 align:middle line:84%
That happens if--
so, there are N

00:52:12.320 --> 00:52:15.960 align:middle line:84%
squared obvious solutions to
this, which are, A1 equals A2.

00:52:15.960 --> 00:52:17.130 align:middle line:90%
And B1 equals B2.

00:52:17.130 --> 00:52:20.080 align:middle line:90%


00:52:20.080 --> 00:52:24.920 align:middle line:84%
And if you have a
random set of integers

00:52:24.920 --> 00:52:26.420 align:middle line:84%
or a random subset
of a big group,

00:52:26.420 --> 00:52:28.920 align:middle line:84%
those might be the
only solutions.

00:52:28.920 --> 00:52:37.570 align:middle line:84%
So, here, we have only
trivial quadruples, OK?

00:52:37.570 --> 00:52:41.090 align:middle line:84%
And energy is at most N
cubed, because once you've

00:52:41.090 --> 00:52:42.890 align:middle line:84%
picked three of
these, the fourth one

00:52:42.890 --> 00:52:44.630 align:middle line:90%
is determined by this equation.

00:52:44.630 --> 00:52:47.690 align:middle line:84%
So there's, at most, N cubed
of these additive quadruples.

00:52:47.690 --> 00:52:58.630 align:middle line:84%
And this happens if A equals
B, equals A subgroup of z.

00:52:58.630 --> 00:53:01.670 align:middle line:90%
A and B are subgroup of z.

00:53:01.670 --> 00:53:03.650 align:middle line:84%
And there's always
a choice of B2

00:53:03.650 --> 00:53:05.480 align:middle line:84%
you can pick to
solve this equation.

00:53:05.480 --> 00:53:09.330 align:middle line:90%


00:53:09.330 --> 00:53:12.490 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

00:53:12.490 --> 00:53:15.010 align:middle line:84%
So, having large
energy is having

00:53:15.010 --> 00:53:16.810 align:middle line:90%
a lot of additive structure.

00:53:16.810 --> 00:53:19.790 align:middle line:84%
And, before, we were thinking
that, if A plus B is small,

00:53:19.790 --> 00:53:23.050 align:middle line:84%
then that would mean there's
a lot of additive structure.

00:53:23.050 --> 00:53:24.870 align:middle line:84%
How are those related
to each other?

00:53:24.870 --> 00:53:44.540 align:middle line:90%


00:53:44.540 --> 00:53:47.246 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:53:47.246 --> 00:53:53.980 align:middle line:84%
So, there's a lemma that says,
A times B, A squared times

00:53:53.980 --> 00:53:57.180 align:middle line:84%
B squared, is, at most,
the size of A plus B,

00:53:57.180 --> 00:54:03.140 align:middle line:84%
times the energy between A
and B. And the proof of this

00:54:03.140 --> 00:54:05.660 align:middle line:90%
is just Cauchy-Schwarz.

00:54:05.660 --> 00:54:13.100 align:middle line:84%
So, if I add up on z, rAB of
z, I get the size of A times

00:54:13.100 --> 00:54:17.400 align:middle line:84%
the size of B. This
is by double counting.

00:54:17.400 --> 00:54:19.920 align:middle line:84%
So, every time I add somebody
in A and somebody in B,

00:54:19.920 --> 00:54:20.840 align:middle line:90%
I get some z.

00:54:20.840 --> 00:54:24.380 align:middle line:84%
I add this up and
get all the pairs.

00:54:24.380 --> 00:54:33.390 align:middle line:84%
So, now, A times B is
the sum, z, of rAB of z.

00:54:33.390 --> 00:54:37.750 align:middle line:84%
And in this sum, I only need
to count the guys in A plus B,

00:54:37.750 --> 00:54:41.530 align:middle line:84%
because z cannot be
written as A plus B at all.

00:54:41.530 --> 00:54:44.710 align:middle line:90%
It means that this was 0.

00:54:44.710 --> 00:54:47.790 align:middle line:90%
Now, I Cauchy-Schwarz.

00:54:47.790 --> 00:54:54.090 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to write it as the
sum for A plus B of 1 to the 1/2

00:54:54.090 --> 00:55:00.490 align:middle line:84%
half, and the sum, rAB
of z squared to the 1/2.

00:55:00.490 --> 00:55:03.710 align:middle line:90%


00:55:03.710 --> 00:55:08.230 align:middle line:84%
So that's the size of
A plus B to the 1/2,

00:55:08.230 --> 00:55:11.565 align:middle line:90%
times the energy to the 1/2.

00:55:11.565 --> 00:55:12.440 align:middle line:90%
And that's the proof.

00:55:12.440 --> 00:55:17.350 align:middle line:90%


00:55:17.350 --> 00:55:18.090 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:55:18.090 --> 00:55:23.330 align:middle line:84%
So we see from this that,
if A plus B is small,

00:55:23.330 --> 00:55:25.230 align:middle line:90%
then the energy must be large.

00:55:25.230 --> 00:55:27.580 align:middle line:84%
We could bring the A plus
B over to the other side.

00:55:27.580 --> 00:55:29.160 align:middle line:90%
So, people usually write this.

00:55:29.160 --> 00:55:40.200 align:middle line:84%
The energy is at least A squared
times B squared, over A plus B.

00:55:40.200 --> 00:55:42.840 align:middle line:84%
So, for instance, if
A and B have size, N,

00:55:42.840 --> 00:55:46.040 align:middle line:84%
and A plus B is almost
N, then the energy

00:55:46.040 --> 00:55:48.120 align:middle line:84%
would be at least
around N cubed,

00:55:48.120 --> 00:55:49.700 align:middle line:90%
which is as big as it could be.

00:55:49.700 --> 00:55:53.000 align:middle line:90%


00:55:53.000 --> 00:55:54.320 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:55:54.320 --> 00:56:02.990 align:middle line:84%
So, A plus B small implies
that the energy is large.

00:56:02.990 --> 00:56:08.720 align:middle line:90%


00:56:08.720 --> 00:56:12.440 align:middle line:84%
Now, do people think you
can go the other way?

00:56:12.440 --> 00:56:14.960 align:middle line:84%
If the energy is
large, does that

00:56:14.960 --> 00:56:16.690 align:middle line:90%
imply that A plus B is small?

00:56:16.690 --> 00:56:25.930 align:middle line:90%


00:56:25.930 --> 00:56:29.850 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: No, because of course,
you can have some garbage.

00:56:29.850 --> 00:56:34.210 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Good, no because
you can have some garbage.

00:56:34.210 --> 00:56:35.010 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:56:35.010 --> 00:56:47.210 align:middle line:84%
So, energy of AB large does not
imply that A plus B is small.

00:56:47.210 --> 00:56:53.530 align:middle line:84%
The example is that A
equals B, equals numbers up

00:56:53.530 --> 00:56:55.970 align:middle line:84%
to N, somebody with a lot
of additive structure,

00:56:55.970 --> 00:56:57.320 align:middle line:90%
union, some garbage.

00:56:57.320 --> 00:57:01.010 align:middle line:90%


00:57:01.010 --> 00:57:01.570 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:57:01.570 --> 00:57:04.010 align:middle line:84%
Now, if you look at the
definition of the energy,

00:57:04.010 --> 00:57:07.110 align:middle line:84%
if I add some extra
elements to A or to B,

00:57:07.110 --> 00:57:10.730 align:middle line:84%
it can only increase the
energy, perhaps not very much.

00:57:10.730 --> 00:57:12.970 align:middle line:84%
So the energy of this
example is at least

00:57:12.970 --> 00:57:16.210 align:middle line:84%
the energy of this
example, which is large.

00:57:16.210 --> 00:57:19.810 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand, the garbage
can make this a lot bigger.

00:57:19.810 --> 00:57:21.530 align:middle line:84%
And this is basically
the same example

00:57:21.530 --> 00:57:24.690 align:middle line:84%
that we've been
grappling with all class.

00:57:24.690 --> 00:57:35.940 align:middle line:90%


00:57:35.940 --> 00:57:40.700 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

00:57:40.700 --> 00:57:44.320 align:middle line:90%
So, now, I'll leave that up.

00:57:44.320 --> 00:58:00.020 align:middle line:90%


00:58:00.020 --> 00:58:02.140 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:58:02.140 --> 00:58:02.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:02.640 --> 00:58:07.593 align:middle line:90%


00:58:07.593 --> 00:58:13.860 align:middle line:84%
Now, if the energy
of A and B is small,

00:58:13.860 --> 00:58:18.320 align:middle line:84%
that implies that the
size of A plus B is large.

00:58:18.320 --> 00:58:21.550 align:middle line:84%
That's just the contrapositive
of what we wrote before,

00:58:21.550 --> 00:58:23.470 align:middle line:84%
or you can see it
from this formula.

00:58:23.470 --> 00:58:24.370 align:middle line:90%
This is small.

00:58:24.370 --> 00:58:25.650 align:middle line:90%
Then this one must be large.

00:58:25.650 --> 00:58:28.550 align:middle line:90%


00:58:28.550 --> 00:58:32.510 align:middle line:90%
Right, OK.

00:58:32.510 --> 00:58:40.670 align:middle line:90%
Now, all right.

00:58:40.670 --> 00:58:45.830 align:middle line:84%
Now, suppose I have a set, x,
in A cross B. And I look at

00:58:45.830 --> 00:58:48.510 align:middle line:90%
pi1 of x.

00:58:48.510 --> 00:58:52.910 align:middle line:84%
So remember that
pi1 of A cross B

00:58:52.910 --> 00:58:58.750 align:middle line:84%
is just A plus B. So when I take
pi1 of x, it's like A plus B.

00:58:58.750 --> 00:59:00.050 align:middle line:90%
But I don't take all the pairs.

00:59:00.050 --> 00:59:01.340 align:middle line:90%
I just take the pairs in x.

00:59:01.340 --> 00:59:14.510 align:middle line:90%


00:59:14.510 --> 00:59:15.050 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:59:15.050 --> 00:59:18.470 align:middle line:90%


00:59:18.470 --> 00:59:25.600 align:middle line:84%
So, even if pi1 of x were
small, if x was a large set

00:59:25.600 --> 00:59:27.880 align:middle line:84%
and pi1 of x were
small, that would still

00:59:27.880 --> 00:59:32.640 align:middle line:84%
produce a lot of energy
because that would still

00:59:32.640 --> 00:59:37.440 align:middle line:84%
be a lot of numbers,
a bunch of numbers,

00:59:37.440 --> 00:59:42.000 align:middle line:84%
z, that have many
representations of A plus B.

00:59:42.000 --> 00:59:44.100 align:middle line:84%
Let me just write it
down OK, so, yeah.

00:59:44.100 --> 00:59:54.760 align:middle line:84%
So, actually, so let me recall
that A plus B large, and x being

00:59:54.760 --> 00:59:59.520 align:middle line:84%
a big fraction of A
times B, that does not

00:59:59.520 --> 01:00:03.743 align:middle line:90%
imply that pi1 of x is large.

01:00:03.743 --> 01:00:05.160 align:middle line:84%
And this is, again,
the main thing

01:00:05.160 --> 01:00:07.820 align:middle line:90%
that we were struggling with.

01:00:07.820 --> 01:00:10.120 align:middle line:90%
But with energy, this is true.

01:00:10.120 --> 01:00:15.580 align:middle line:84%
So, lemma, let me check
exactly what it says.

01:00:15.580 --> 01:00:25.650 align:middle line:90%


01:00:25.650 --> 01:00:26.850 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:00:26.850 --> 01:00:31.330 align:middle line:84%
So, lemma, x
squared is less than

01:00:31.330 --> 01:00:35.540 align:middle line:84%
or equal to pi 1 of x,
times the energy of AB.

01:00:35.540 --> 01:00:39.570 align:middle line:90%


01:00:39.570 --> 01:00:43.730 align:middle line:84%
So if the energy
is small, then pi 1

01:00:43.730 --> 01:00:46.090 align:middle line:84%
of x is pretty big
for every subset, x,

01:00:46.090 --> 01:00:47.750 align:middle line:90%
for every large subset, x.

01:00:47.750 --> 01:00:51.130 align:middle line:90%


01:00:51.130 --> 01:00:54.730 align:middle line:84%
The proof is almost the
same as the previous proof.

01:00:54.730 --> 01:00:59.490 align:middle line:84%
So, proof, rx of z
is the number of ways

01:00:59.490 --> 01:01:06.130 align:middle line:84%
of writing A plus B equal to
z, where the pair, AB, is in x.

01:01:06.130 --> 01:01:10.090 align:middle line:84%
And that's smaller than
representations of z

01:01:10.090 --> 01:01:12.850 align:middle line:84%
as a general sum of
sum between A and B,

01:01:12.850 --> 01:01:18.370 align:middle line:84%
because we're only taking
a portion of the sums.

01:01:18.370 --> 01:01:19.490 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:01:19.490 --> 01:01:26.430 align:middle line:84%
So, now, x is the
sum on z of rx of z.

01:01:26.430 --> 01:01:30.690 align:middle line:90%


01:01:30.690 --> 01:01:36.570 align:middle line:84%
And, here, in this sum, we only
have to take z's in pi 1 of x.

01:01:36.570 --> 01:01:38.530 align:middle line:84%
We only have to consider
those z's that can

01:01:38.530 --> 01:01:43.210 align:middle line:84%
be written as the form, A plus
B, where A and B are in x.

01:01:43.210 --> 01:01:45.810 align:middle line:84%
So, now, we can
Cauchy-Schwarz this.

01:01:45.810 --> 01:01:53.710 align:middle line:84%
And we get the size, pi1 of x to
the 1/2, times an energy thing,

01:01:53.710 --> 01:01:55.970 align:middle line:84%
which is smaller than
the standard energy.

01:01:55.970 --> 01:02:00.850 align:middle line:84%
So we have the sum, rx
of z squared to the 1/2.

01:02:00.850 --> 01:02:04.797 align:middle line:84%
That's smaller than the sum
rAB of z squared to the 1/2,

01:02:04.797 --> 01:02:05.880 align:middle line:90%
which gives us the energy.

01:02:05.880 --> 01:02:12.210 align:middle line:90%


01:02:12.210 --> 01:02:13.390 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

01:02:13.390 --> 01:02:18.060 align:middle line:84%
So to summarize,
having small energy

01:02:18.060 --> 01:02:20.580 align:middle line:84%
implies that the
sum set is large.

01:02:20.580 --> 01:02:22.360 align:middle line:90%
But it's stronger than that.

01:02:22.360 --> 01:02:26.780 align:middle line:84%
And it also implies
that pi1 of x

01:02:26.780 --> 01:02:31.220 align:middle line:84%
is large for all substantial
subsets of A cross B.

01:02:31.220 --> 01:02:33.580 align:middle line:84%
So it's stronger, in a way,
which is exactly what we

01:02:33.580 --> 01:02:34.880 align:middle line:90%
needed in our discussion.

01:02:34.880 --> 01:02:38.380 align:middle line:90%


01:02:38.380 --> 01:02:45.500 align:middle line:84%
So that suggests a better
version of theorem 1

01:02:45.500 --> 01:02:46.930 align:middle line:84%
that we could have
tried to prove.

01:02:46.930 --> 01:02:51.660 align:middle line:90%


01:02:51.660 --> 01:02:52.710 align:middle line:90%
Let's erase this lemma.

01:02:52.710 --> 01:02:56.620 align:middle line:90%


01:02:56.620 --> 01:02:59.020 align:middle line:84%
So, remember, theorem
1 said that, if we

01:02:59.020 --> 01:03:04.100 align:middle line:84%
take the projection of A cross A
in many directions, one of them

01:03:04.100 --> 01:03:07.740 align:middle line:90%
has a large cardinality.

01:03:07.740 --> 01:03:09.220 align:middle line:84%
But we could have
proved, we could

01:03:09.220 --> 01:03:11.700 align:middle line:84%
have tried to prove something
stronger, that one of them

01:03:11.700 --> 01:03:13.215 align:middle line:90%
has a small energy.

01:03:13.215 --> 01:03:14.090 align:middle line:90%
Let me write it down.

01:03:14.090 --> 01:03:14.730 align:middle line:90%
It's true.

01:03:14.730 --> 01:03:17.150 align:middle line:90%
And it's a theorem.

01:03:17.150 --> 01:03:26.310 align:middle line:90%
Theorem 2 says-- all right.

01:03:26.310 --> 01:03:32.050 align:middle line:84%
So if A is a subset of Fp,
size of A is p to the SA,

01:03:32.050 --> 01:03:37.910 align:middle line:84%
0 less than SA, less
than 1 D is in Fp.

01:03:37.910 --> 01:03:40.776 align:middle line:90%
Size of D is p to the SD.

01:03:40.776 --> 01:03:43.950 align:middle line:90%
0 is less than SD.

01:03:43.950 --> 01:03:49.110 align:middle line:84%
Then I'm going to consider
all the directions

01:03:49.110 --> 01:03:50.950 align:middle line:90%
and pick the best one.

01:03:50.950 --> 01:03:55.430 align:middle line:84%
And instead of looking
at the size of A plus TA,

01:03:55.430 --> 01:04:00.270 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to look at the
energy of A, comma TA.

01:04:00.270 --> 01:04:04.510 align:middle line:84%
And I'll take the
minimum over all the T.

01:04:04.510 --> 01:04:05.070 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:04:05.070 --> 01:04:10.190 align:middle line:84%
So, the biggest this energy
could be is p to the 3SA.

01:04:10.190 --> 01:04:13.282 align:middle line:84%
It's the maximum
possible energy.

01:04:13.282 --> 01:04:15.740 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to say, it's
a little bit better than this.

01:04:15.740 --> 01:04:27.560 align:middle line:90%


01:04:27.560 --> 01:04:35.480 align:middle line:84%
Now, because of this
lemma, we automatically

01:04:35.480 --> 01:04:40.320 align:middle line:84%
get not only a lower bound
on pi T of A cross A.

01:04:40.320 --> 01:04:44.480 align:middle line:84%
But we get a lower bound on pi T
of any big subset of A cross A.

01:04:44.480 --> 01:04:47.450 align:middle line:84%
So, this automatically
gives the BKT theorem.

01:04:47.450 --> 01:04:50.960 align:middle line:90%


01:04:50.960 --> 01:04:54.760 align:middle line:84%
So, in fact, this easily
implies a strong version

01:04:54.760 --> 01:05:00.200 align:middle line:84%
of the BKT theorem, which I
think was also proven by BKT.

01:05:00.200 --> 01:05:03.090 align:middle line:90%
And it says that--

01:05:03.090 --> 01:05:07.000 align:middle line:90%


01:05:07.000 --> 01:05:11.690 align:middle line:90%
so, sorry.

01:05:11.690 --> 01:05:14.650 align:middle line:90%
x is p to the sx.

01:05:14.650 --> 01:05:18.650 align:middle line:90%
And D is as above.

01:05:18.650 --> 01:05:24.620 align:middle line:84%
So, not only you can say, the
maximum T and D, pi T of x

01:05:24.620 --> 01:05:25.120 align:middle line:90%
is large.

01:05:25.120 --> 01:05:30.690 align:middle line:90%


01:05:30.690 --> 01:05:34.730 align:middle line:90%
So, that's the regular theorem.

01:05:34.730 --> 01:05:39.410 align:middle line:84%
And this follows from theorem
2, and using our lemma.

01:05:39.410 --> 01:05:41.410 align:middle line:90%
But we could say that--

01:05:41.410 --> 01:05:46.610 align:middle line:90%


01:05:46.610 --> 01:05:48.390 align:middle line:90%
so, this is true.

01:05:48.390 --> 01:05:59.610 align:middle line:84%
But, even better, there is
some T and D so that, if y--

01:05:59.610 --> 01:06:07.020 align:middle line:84%
so if y is a subset of x and
it's a substantial subset of x,

01:06:07.020 --> 01:06:12.120 align:middle line:90%
then pi T of y is big.

01:06:12.120 --> 01:06:19.260 align:middle line:90%


01:06:19.260 --> 01:06:20.180 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:06:20.180 --> 01:06:24.380 align:middle line:84%
So, the proof from here to
here, we observed earlier

01:06:24.380 --> 01:06:29.180 align:middle line:90%
that we can reduce to the case.

01:06:29.180 --> 01:06:31.820 align:middle line:90%
Well, OK.

01:06:31.820 --> 01:06:34.200 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, I guess I should say,
using Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers,

01:06:34.200 --> 01:06:36.300 align:middle line:84%
we could reduce
to the case where

01:06:36.300 --> 01:06:41.720 align:middle line:84%
x is a big subset of A cross A.
And then y is a big subset of x.

01:06:41.720 --> 01:06:43.820 align:middle line:84%
So y is a big
subset of A cross A.

01:06:43.820 --> 01:06:48.575 align:middle line:84%
And then you use the
energy bound to get this.

01:06:48.575 --> 01:06:49.075 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:06:49.075 --> 01:06:51.805 align:middle line:90%


01:06:51.805 --> 01:07:00.000 align:middle line:84%
So, then, we say, proof
of theorem 2 plus BKT2

01:07:00.000 --> 01:07:01.890 align:middle line:84%
are similar to what
we did in class.

01:07:01.890 --> 01:07:09.510 align:middle line:90%


01:07:09.510 --> 01:07:14.830 align:middle line:84%
So, they could be good optional
exercises, or some pieces of it

01:07:14.830 --> 01:07:17.570 align:middle line:90%
might be required exercises.

01:07:17.570 --> 01:07:27.658 align:middle line:90%


01:07:27.658 --> 01:07:29.308 align:middle line:84%
And I thought I
should mention this.

01:07:29.308 --> 01:07:31.350 align:middle line:84%
One of the things that
Pablo impressed on me when

01:07:31.350 --> 01:07:33.350 align:middle line:84%
we were talking over
the vacation week

01:07:33.350 --> 01:07:36.910 align:middle line:84%
was that this slightly
stronger version

01:07:36.910 --> 01:07:40.055 align:middle line:90%
is important in applications.

01:07:40.055 --> 01:07:41.430 align:middle line:84%
Most of the
applications actually

01:07:41.430 --> 01:07:44.130 align:middle line:84%
depend on being able to say
the slightly stronger thing.

01:07:44.130 --> 01:07:49.630 align:middle line:90%


01:07:49.630 --> 01:07:53.810 align:middle line:90%
OK OK.

01:07:53.810 --> 01:07:59.470 align:middle line:84%
So, now, you might think,
you might ask yourself,

01:07:59.470 --> 01:08:02.190 align:middle line:84%
maybe energy is
actually a better thing

01:08:02.190 --> 01:08:05.680 align:middle line:84%
to be talking about because
a bound for the energy

01:08:05.680 --> 01:08:08.270 align:middle line:84%
is kind of stable,
undertaking large subsets.

01:08:08.270 --> 01:08:11.080 align:middle line:90%


01:08:11.080 --> 01:08:14.000 align:middle line:84%
And so, maybe, we should have
been talking about energy

01:08:14.000 --> 01:08:15.680 align:middle line:90%
all along.

01:08:15.680 --> 01:08:19.660 align:middle line:84%
And it's reasonable to ask, if
you take our proof of theorem 1

01:08:19.660 --> 01:08:22.840 align:middle line:84%
and you just try to change all
the cardinalities to energies,

01:08:22.840 --> 01:08:25.990 align:middle line:84%
could you adapt it and
prove theorem 2, instead?

01:08:25.990 --> 01:08:28.880 align:middle line:90%


01:08:28.880 --> 01:08:32.319 align:middle line:90%
And you can't do that.

01:08:32.319 --> 01:08:36.300 align:middle line:84%
And it's a good moment to recap
the main idea in theorem 1,

01:08:36.300 --> 01:08:41.240 align:middle line:84%
and also a way of reflecting
on the different big tools

01:08:41.240 --> 01:08:42.899 align:middle line:84%
and how they're
related to each other.

01:08:42.899 --> 01:08:47.560 align:middle line:90%


01:08:47.560 --> 01:08:48.800 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:08:48.800 --> 01:08:51.279 align:middle line:90%
Let's look at this.

01:08:51.279 --> 01:08:53.549 align:middle line:84%
Maybe, now, I can
erase the BSG theorem.

01:08:53.549 --> 01:09:02.710 align:middle line:90%


01:09:02.710 --> 01:09:03.210 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:09:03.210 --> 01:09:05.149 align:middle line:84%
Actually, before I
erase the BSG theorem,

01:09:05.149 --> 01:09:06.890 align:middle line:84%
let me make a little
comment about it.

01:09:06.890 --> 01:09:10.250 align:middle line:84%
So, there are a couple
of closely-related forms

01:09:10.250 --> 01:09:10.910 align:middle line:90%
of the theorem.

01:09:10.910 --> 01:09:14.370 align:middle line:84%
And another way I often say it
is that, if the energy of AB

01:09:14.370 --> 01:09:18.310 align:middle line:84%
is large, then there must
be A prime and B prime,

01:09:18.310 --> 01:09:21.040 align:middle line:84%
so that the cardinality of A
prime plus B prime is small.

01:09:21.040 --> 01:09:24.130 align:middle line:90%


01:09:24.130 --> 01:09:25.609 align:middle line:90%
Maybe I should write it, yeah.

01:09:25.609 --> 01:09:29.316 align:middle line:90%


01:09:29.316 --> 01:09:30.790 align:middle line:90%
Let me put it here.

01:09:30.790 --> 01:09:36.930 align:middle line:90%


01:09:36.930 --> 01:09:42.290 align:middle line:90%
So, theorem BSG variant.

01:09:42.290 --> 01:09:44.750 align:middle line:84%
This is the way it's
most commonly said.

01:09:44.750 --> 01:09:48.090 align:middle line:84%
So I would be a bit remiss
not to show it to you.

01:09:48.090 --> 01:09:53.250 align:middle line:84%
So if A and B are
in an abelian group,

01:09:53.250 --> 01:09:59.130 align:middle line:84%
and let's say A and B have size,
at most, N. And the energy of AB

01:09:59.130 --> 01:09:59.660 align:middle line:90%
is large.

01:09:59.660 --> 01:10:02.460 align:middle line:90%


01:10:02.460 --> 01:10:08.700 align:middle line:84%
Energy of AB is greater
than A inverse N cubed.

01:10:08.700 --> 01:10:11.740 align:middle line:84%
Then it may not be
the case that A plus B

01:10:11.740 --> 01:10:14.420 align:middle line:84%
is small because of the
example with garbage.

01:10:14.420 --> 01:10:17.000 align:middle line:84%
But we can get rid
of the garbage.

01:10:17.000 --> 01:10:24.920 align:middle line:84%
So there exists A prime in A and
B prime in B, so that A prime--

01:10:24.920 --> 01:10:28.300 align:middle line:90%


01:10:28.300 --> 01:10:31.100 align:middle line:84%
yes, so that they
are substantial.

01:10:31.100 --> 01:10:37.020 align:middle line:84%
So, A prime and B prime are
greater than or equal to K

01:10:37.020 --> 01:10:39.460 align:middle line:90%
to the minus order of 1n.

01:10:39.460 --> 01:10:45.180 align:middle line:84%
And A prime plus B prime is less
than or equal to K to the order

01:10:45.180 --> 01:10:47.420 align:middle line:90%
of 1N.

01:10:47.420 --> 01:10:50.620 align:middle line:84%
So if we can locate the
correct structured parts,

01:10:50.620 --> 01:10:53.910 align:middle line:84%
then their subset is small,
after we remove some garbage.

01:10:53.910 --> 01:10:56.780 align:middle line:90%


01:10:56.780 --> 01:10:58.760 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, OK.

01:10:58.760 --> 01:11:06.390 align:middle line:90%


01:11:06.390 --> 01:11:07.090 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:11:07.090 --> 01:11:09.750 align:middle line:84%
So, now, let me
remind you of one

01:11:09.750 --> 01:11:12.770 align:middle line:84%
of the key ideas in
the proof of theorem 1.

01:11:12.770 --> 01:11:21.670 align:middle line:90%


01:11:21.670 --> 01:11:28.430 align:middle line:84%
Key idea in the
proof of theorem 1.

01:11:28.430 --> 01:11:32.430 align:middle line:84%
So, the key idea was based on
the Plünnecke-Ruzsa inequality.

01:11:32.430 --> 01:11:36.530 align:middle line:84%
And it was an idea that I
called, contagious structure.

01:11:36.530 --> 01:11:39.630 align:middle line:90%


01:11:39.630 --> 01:11:52.550 align:middle line:84%
So, it's said, if A plus T1a is
small and A plus T2a is small,

01:11:52.550 --> 01:12:00.360 align:middle line:84%
then A plus T1 plus
T2a is also small--

01:12:00.360 --> 01:12:02.870 align:middle line:84%
not quite as small,
but still pretty small.

01:12:02.870 --> 01:12:06.240 align:middle line:90%


01:12:06.240 --> 01:12:07.240 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:12:07.240 --> 01:12:10.560 align:middle line:90%
So, this was the key thing.

01:12:10.560 --> 01:12:16.760 align:middle line:84%
If A plus TA is small
for a bunch of T and D,

01:12:16.760 --> 01:12:19.440 align:middle line:84%
then it would have to be small
for an even bigger set of D

01:12:19.440 --> 01:12:23.800 align:middle line:84%
by adding D, or by multiplying
D, or by taking negatives.

01:12:23.800 --> 01:12:25.840 align:middle line:84%
And then there would be
a huge set of T's, where

01:12:25.840 --> 01:12:27.400 align:middle line:90%
A plus TA was small.

01:12:27.400 --> 01:12:31.080 align:middle line:84%
And then that contradicts
basic double counting.

01:12:31.080 --> 01:12:32.520 align:middle line:90%
That was the proof.

01:12:32.520 --> 01:12:33.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:12:33.640 --> 01:12:37.960 align:middle line:84%
So, what if we tried to
work with energy throughout?

01:12:37.960 --> 01:12:42.960 align:middle line:84%
So, instead of trying to
prove that A plus TA is big,

01:12:42.960 --> 01:12:46.872 align:middle line:84%
we're going to try to prove
that the energy is small.

01:12:46.872 --> 01:12:48.580 align:middle line:84%
So, we're doing a
proof by contradiction.

01:12:48.580 --> 01:12:51.160 align:middle line:84%
So the analogous
question would be,

01:12:51.160 --> 01:12:56.720 align:middle line:84%
if the energy between
A and T1 of A is large,

01:12:56.720 --> 01:13:02.080 align:middle line:84%
and the energy between
A and T2 of A is large,

01:13:02.080 --> 01:13:09.360 align:middle line:84%
then does that imply that the
energy between A and T1 plus T2A

01:13:09.360 --> 01:13:09.970 align:middle line:90%
is large?

01:13:09.970 --> 01:13:20.520 align:middle line:90%


01:13:20.520 --> 01:13:21.600 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:13:21.600 --> 01:13:23.880 align:middle line:90%
The answer is no.

01:13:23.880 --> 01:13:29.040 align:middle line:84%
And it is the same issue that
we saw before, that when we say,

01:13:29.040 --> 01:13:32.940 align:middle line:84%
the energy is large, it means
there's at least a piece of A

01:13:32.940 --> 01:13:36.600 align:middle line:84%
and a piece of T1A that are
very friendly with each other.

01:13:36.600 --> 01:13:39.120 align:middle line:84%
But it doesn't have
to be all of them.

01:13:39.120 --> 01:13:43.480 align:middle line:84%
So, one piece of A must
be very friendly with T1A.

01:13:43.480 --> 01:13:48.120 align:middle line:84%
And one piece of A must
be very friendly with T2A.

01:13:48.120 --> 01:13:51.900 align:middle line:84%
But those could be two different
pieces of A. And in that case,

01:13:51.900 --> 01:13:54.355 align:middle line:84%
we can't really
learn anything more.

01:13:54.355 --> 01:13:56.530 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't mean there's
any piece of A that's

01:13:56.530 --> 01:13:59.010 align:middle line:90%
friendly with both of them.

01:13:59.010 --> 01:14:00.430 align:middle line:90%
So, here's the example.

01:14:00.430 --> 01:14:02.770 align:middle line:90%
The answer is no.

01:14:02.770 --> 01:14:04.250 align:middle line:90%
Here's the example.

01:14:04.250 --> 01:14:08.890 align:middle line:84%
So, A might be the
numbers up to N, union T1

01:14:08.890 --> 01:14:15.106 align:middle line:84%
times the numbers up to N, union
T2 times the numbers up to N.

01:14:15.106 --> 01:14:16.570 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:14:16.570 --> 01:14:20.930 align:middle line:84%
So, then, T1A would
be T1 numbers up

01:14:20.930 --> 01:14:23.090 align:middle line:90%
to N union, dot, dot, dot.

01:14:23.090 --> 01:14:28.850 align:middle line:84%
T2A is T2 numbers up to
N, union, dot, dot, dot.

01:14:28.850 --> 01:14:32.490 align:middle line:84%
So, these two guys
are very friendly,

01:14:32.490 --> 01:14:34.670 align:middle line:84%
not just because they're
the same as each other.

01:14:34.670 --> 01:14:36.420 align:middle line:84%
Not everybody who's
the same as each other

01:14:36.420 --> 01:14:39.370 align:middle line:84%
is friends, but
because they have

01:14:39.370 --> 01:14:41.930 align:middle line:90%
a lot of additive structures.

01:14:41.930 --> 01:14:47.530 align:middle line:84%
And, therefore,
this guy is large.

01:14:47.530 --> 01:14:54.740 align:middle line:84%
And these two guys
are very friendly.

01:14:54.740 --> 01:14:59.100 align:middle line:84%
And therefore,
this guy is large.

01:14:59.100 --> 01:15:03.360 align:middle line:84%
But there's nothing
going on with T1.

01:15:03.360 --> 01:15:05.660 align:middle line:84%
Plus, T1 and T2 are
totally arbitrary.

01:15:05.660 --> 01:15:09.360 align:middle line:84%
T1 plus T2, we would not
typically have this large.

01:15:09.360 --> 01:15:12.660 align:middle line:90%


01:15:12.660 --> 01:15:16.740 align:middle line:90%
So, all right.

01:15:16.740 --> 01:15:21.790 align:middle line:84%
If a, T1 plus T2A
is typically small.

01:15:21.790 --> 01:15:25.620 align:middle line:90%


01:15:25.620 --> 01:15:28.460 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

01:15:28.460 --> 01:15:33.060 align:middle line:84%
So it was actually kind of
crucial in our proof of theorem

01:15:33.060 --> 01:15:37.060 align:middle line:84%
1 to talk about the cardinality
of the subset instead

01:15:37.060 --> 01:15:39.380 align:middle line:84%
of the energy because,
in that setting,

01:15:39.380 --> 01:15:41.900 align:middle line:84%
we have the Plünnecke-Ruzsa
inequalities.

01:15:41.900 --> 01:15:44.020 align:middle line:84%
And we get a great
deal of structure

01:15:44.020 --> 01:15:45.660 align:middle line:84%
from a single
subset being small.

01:15:45.660 --> 01:15:48.460 align:middle line:90%
We get lots of other things.

01:15:48.460 --> 01:15:53.870 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand, it is nice,
eventually, to get to theorem 2,

01:15:53.870 --> 01:15:55.910 align:middle line:90%
because theorem 2 is stable.

01:15:55.910 --> 01:15:57.630 align:middle line:84%
If you replace the
actual product,

01:15:57.630 --> 01:16:03.050 align:middle line:84%
A cross A, by a subset,
which is almost all of it.

01:16:03.050 --> 01:16:06.550 align:middle line:84%
So, both looking at cardinality
and looking at energy

01:16:06.550 --> 01:16:08.830 align:middle line:90%
have good features.

01:16:08.830 --> 01:16:11.830 align:middle line:84%
Energy estimates are
stable, undertaking subsets.

01:16:11.830 --> 01:16:15.190 align:middle line:84%
And the cardinality estimates
have this contagious structure

01:16:15.190 --> 01:16:15.913 align:middle line:90%
thing.

01:16:15.913 --> 01:16:17.080 align:middle line:90%
Those are both very helpful.

01:16:17.080 --> 01:16:22.710 align:middle line:90%


01:16:22.710 --> 01:16:29.070 align:middle line:84%
And Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers,
this is important

01:16:29.070 --> 01:16:33.750 align:middle line:84%
because, even though
having a big energy

01:16:33.750 --> 01:16:36.430 align:middle line:84%
is not synonymous with
having a small subset,

01:16:36.430 --> 01:16:39.350 align:middle line:84%
Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers says
they're very closely-related.

01:16:39.350 --> 01:16:41.190 align:middle line:84%
And so, by using
Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers,

01:16:41.190 --> 01:16:44.430 align:middle line:84%
you can often get the
best of both worlds.

01:16:44.430 --> 01:16:46.190 align:middle line:84%
So if you were to
pretend that you

01:16:46.190 --> 01:16:49.920 align:middle line:84%
could have all the good
features of an energy bound,

01:16:49.920 --> 01:16:51.970 align:middle line:84%
and all the good features
of a cardinality bound

01:16:51.970 --> 01:16:54.040 align:middle line:84%
to see what you could
prove, very often,

01:16:54.040 --> 01:16:57.320 align:middle line:84%
you can prove those things by
using Balog-Szemeredi-Gowers

01:16:57.320 --> 01:16:58.430 align:middle line:90%
to move back and forth.

01:16:58.430 --> 01:17:04.040 align:middle line:90%


01:17:04.040 --> 01:17:06.843 align:middle line:84%
Pablo gave the analysis
seminar a few weeks ago.

01:17:06.843 --> 01:17:08.760 align:middle line:84%
And he gave an overview
of recent developments

01:17:08.760 --> 01:17:10.400 align:middle line:90%
in projection theory.

01:17:10.400 --> 01:17:13.200 align:middle line:84%
And he made the
claim, or suggestion,

01:17:13.200 --> 01:17:16.240 align:middle line:84%
that this theorem might be one
of the most important or most

01:17:16.240 --> 01:17:20.480 align:middle line:84%
used theorems in math in
the last several decades.

01:17:20.480 --> 01:17:24.160 align:middle line:90%
It was a little provocative.

01:17:24.160 --> 01:17:26.160 align:middle line:90%
I thought it was interesting.

01:17:26.160 --> 01:17:30.580 align:middle line:84%
And I have gradually been
appreciating it more and more.

01:17:30.580 --> 01:17:32.120 align:middle line:90%
I'm learning about it.

01:17:32.120 --> 01:17:36.040 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, I've been gradually
appreciating it more and more.

01:17:36.040 --> 01:17:38.260 align:middle line:84%
And, yeah, probably,
as we keep going,

01:17:38.260 --> 01:17:41.890 align:middle line:84%
we'll see how this
keeps being important.

01:17:41.890 --> 01:17:48.000 align:middle line:90%